1
00:00:10,385 --> 00:00:12,344
YONG-JIN WALKING INTO AN OPEN LOT,
NOT THE HEADQUARTERS

2
00:00:12,345 --> 00:00:13,263
I get it now.

3
00:00:14,347 --> 00:00:15,389
You want me in the car?

4
00:00:15,390 --> 00:00:18,392
HOPPING INTO THE DRIVER'S SEAT

5
00:00:18,393 --> 00:00:22,396
I came to the lot as instructed.

6
00:00:22,397 --> 00:00:25,232
Do we have to drive somewhere?

7
00:00:25,233 --> 00:00:26,358
Where are the others?

8
00:00:26,359 --> 00:00:28,360
GABEE ARRIVES

9
00:00:28,361 --> 00:00:30,321
There's our "Gae-bee."

10
00:00:34,284 --> 00:00:35,492
FULL OF BUBBLY ENERGY

11
00:00:35,493 --> 00:00:36,703
- Hello.
- Hey.

12
00:00:40,832 --> 00:00:41,999
Your clothes--

13
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:44,168
It's in the same shade
as the car's interior.

14
00:00:44,169 --> 00:00:45,628
- I know.
- How did this happen?

15
00:00:46,254 --> 00:00:48,881
- I guess they matched them.
- It's in the seat cover's color.

16
00:00:48,882 --> 00:00:49,798
Exactly.

17
00:00:49,799 --> 00:00:52,134
- Did you get the note too?
- Yes, it told me to come here.

18
00:00:52,135 --> 00:00:53,594
- The address led us here.
- Yes.

19
00:00:53,595 --> 00:00:56,346
ONE MORE PERSON APPROACHES
USING THE SAME ADDRESS AS HIS GUIDE

20
00:00:56,347 --> 00:00:58,348
JOHN PARK ARRIVES

21
00:00:58,349 --> 00:00:59,517
Hey, John's here.

22
00:01:01,019 --> 00:01:02,436
John!

23
00:01:02,437 --> 00:01:03,938
We're here, John.

24
00:01:06,316 --> 00:01:07,859
Why does he look so youthful?

25
00:01:08,359 --> 00:01:10,778
JOHN PARK IS LOOKING
ESPECIALLY YOUNG TODAY

26
00:01:10,779 --> 00:01:14,114
It's obviously nice to see you, John.
But I must say you look so fresh today.

27
00:01:14,115 --> 00:01:15,574
- Me?
- Did you…

28
00:01:15,575 --> 00:01:16,533
It's the glasses.

29
00:01:16,534 --> 00:01:17,993
You got some work done, no?

30
00:01:17,994 --> 00:01:20,162
- I bet you've done Ultherapy.
- Of course not.

31
00:01:20,163 --> 00:01:22,581
It's because I have bangs
and glasses today.

32
00:01:22,582 --> 00:01:24,541
<i>-Really? You look so youthful.
- It must be the bangs.</i>

33
00:01:24,542 --> 00:01:26,002
- It's just an illusion.
- An illusion?

34
00:01:26,544 --> 00:01:29,505
At any rate, this parking lot
has become our new rendezvous point.

35
00:01:29,506 --> 00:01:31,715
- It's because of the explosion.
- We lost our headquarters.

36
00:01:31,716 --> 00:01:36,303
THEIR HEADQUARTERS
WERE BLOWN UP SPECTACULARLY

37
00:01:36,304 --> 00:01:38,138
About that rhythm game,

38
00:01:38,139 --> 00:01:40,224
I thought it over on my way home,
and it made me so mad.

39
00:01:40,225 --> 00:01:41,141
I feel you.

40
00:01:41,142 --> 00:01:44,394
SURE OF THEIR SUCCESS,
THEY LET THEIR GUARDS DOWN

41
00:01:44,395 --> 00:01:47,689
ONLY TO BE HIT BY A SURPRISE ATTACK

42
00:01:47,690 --> 00:01:52,903
BITTER MEMORY OF ROARING IN REGRET
AFTER CELEBRATING TOO EARLY

43
00:01:52,904 --> 00:01:53,946
I nearly lost it.

44
00:01:53,947 --> 00:01:55,447
I'm a dancer, you know.

45
00:01:55,448 --> 00:01:57,867
- Yes, that made me even angrier.
- It really got to me.

46
00:01:58,535 --> 00:02:00,911
SPRING IN EVERY STEP

47
00:02:00,912 --> 00:02:02,329
Hey, Karina's here.

48
00:02:02,330 --> 00:02:05,249
APPROACHING THE VAN
IN THE SAME WAY AS GABEE

49
00:02:05,250 --> 00:02:06,667
What now? Are the windows tinted?

50
00:02:06,668 --> 00:02:08,752
- Super heavily.
- Oh, really?

51
00:02:08,753 --> 00:02:10,754
- Are the windows tinted?
- I can see your silhouettes.

52
00:02:10,755 --> 00:02:12,131
Is that right?

53
00:02:12,132 --> 00:02:14,091
You live up to your nickname, Team Porter.

54
00:02:14,092 --> 00:02:16,135
- I brought a backpack.
- Hey, so you did.

55
00:02:16,136 --> 00:02:17,469
I even brought some snacks.

56
00:02:17,470 --> 00:02:18,762
- Really?
- Yes.

57
00:02:18,763 --> 00:02:20,849
- I got super hungry.
- I craved something sweet too.

58
00:02:21,641 --> 00:02:23,935
What's this?
Has everybody arrived already?

59
00:02:25,979 --> 00:02:27,020
Hey, it's Gabee.

60
00:02:27,021 --> 00:02:28,272
You know what, Gabee?

61
00:02:28,273 --> 00:02:29,481
- Hye-ri.
- It's incredible.

62
00:02:29,482 --> 00:02:31,567
The windshield doesn't show a thing,

63
00:02:31,568 --> 00:02:33,569
but I can still see your teeth!

64
00:02:33,570 --> 00:02:35,445
- This is insane.
- Don't lie to me.

65
00:02:35,446 --> 00:02:36,530
That can't be true.

66
00:02:36,531 --> 00:02:38,448
It's the truth.
I wish I could take a picture of this.

67
00:02:38,449 --> 00:02:39,658
- I mean it.
- Seriously?

68
00:02:39,659 --> 00:02:41,535
It looks dark when the doors are closed.

69
00:02:41,536 --> 00:02:44,163
- I don't buy it.
- But I can still see your teeth.

70
00:02:44,164 --> 00:02:46,623
- I mean it.
- Didn't your dentist say anything…

71
00:02:46,624 --> 00:02:48,418
- Right?
-…against the procedure?

72
00:02:49,043 --> 00:02:50,669
Why didn't my dentist stop me?

73
00:02:50,670 --> 00:02:52,963
- Hello.
- Welcome.

74
00:02:52,964 --> 00:02:55,340
- Hi, Hye-ri.
- Goodness.

75
00:02:55,341 --> 00:02:56,717
You look good today.

76
00:02:56,718 --> 00:02:58,093
- You're glowing.
- Okay.

77
00:02:58,094 --> 00:03:00,220
- We've got a great vibe going today.
- All right!

78
00:03:00,221 --> 00:03:02,891
SCURRYING

79
00:03:04,392 --> 00:03:06,226
HE'S GIVING US DÉJÀ VU

80
00:03:06,227 --> 00:03:09,146
- Are you the XIN agents?
- Of course.

81
00:03:09,147 --> 00:03:11,857
Can't you tell at a glaze…
I mean, at a glance?

82
00:03:11,858 --> 00:03:13,191
You're with the XIN, right?

83
00:03:13,192 --> 00:03:14,109
ALL AGENTS GATHERED

84
00:03:14,110 --> 00:03:16,778
- Is this our new headquarters?
- Well…

85
00:03:16,779 --> 00:03:18,906
- We're supposed to go somewhere…
- Because the Chamber blew up?

86
00:03:18,907 --> 00:03:19,990
…but they didn't tell us where.

87
00:03:19,991 --> 00:03:21,700
- What about this address?
- That's this place.

88
00:03:21,701 --> 00:03:22,910
THAT'S THE PARKING LOT'S ADDRESS

89
00:03:22,911 --> 00:03:25,412
We don't know where we have to go next.

90
00:03:25,413 --> 00:03:27,372
Are we being tested from the start?

91
00:03:27,373 --> 00:03:29,458
Doesn't the navigation system have logs?

92
00:03:29,459 --> 00:03:31,460
Let's see if there are clues.

93
00:03:31,461 --> 00:03:33,630
- They probably left clues.
- Are we jumping right in?

94
00:03:34,464 --> 00:03:36,965
- What could this be?
- Take a look around.

95
00:03:36,966 --> 00:03:38,050
We can start from here.

96
00:03:38,051 --> 00:03:40,427
- Can you open the glove box?
- Do we have to get to work already?

97
00:03:40,428 --> 00:03:41,553
- Found it!
- It's here.

98
00:03:41,554 --> 00:03:43,305
A MANILA FOLDER INSIDE THE GLOVE BOX

99
00:03:43,306 --> 00:03:45,307
- There we have it.
- What is it?

100
00:03:45,308 --> 00:03:47,142
What's going on?

101
00:03:47,143 --> 00:03:49,729
- Turns out the game has already begun.
- You're right.

102
00:03:51,648 --> 00:03:53,857
- We have this…
- What's that?

103
00:03:53,858 --> 00:03:55,025
INCHON'S FLOOD CONTROL GUIDELINE

104
00:03:55,026 --> 00:03:58,403
Look, this is Inchon's guideline
on flood control.

105
00:03:58,404 --> 00:03:59,529
- There's a card too.
- My gosh.

106
00:03:59,530 --> 00:04:00,489
It's brand new.

107
00:04:00,490 --> 00:04:01,740
What's this for?

108
00:04:01,741 --> 00:04:04,493
Compared to last year's precipitation…

109
00:04:04,494 --> 00:04:06,913
Perhaps the card will reveal
hidden clues on the document?

110
00:04:07,580 --> 00:04:09,082
Isn't this a Hi-Pass card?

111
00:04:09,582 --> 00:04:12,709
HYE-RI STUDIES THE DOCUMENT CLOSELY

112
00:04:12,710 --> 00:04:14,503
If you take a look here…

113
00:04:14,504 --> 00:04:15,420
What's it about?

114
00:04:15,421 --> 00:04:18,257
Can you summarize it like an AI assistant?

115
00:04:18,258 --> 00:04:19,675
- I sure can.
- Okay.

116
00:04:19,676 --> 00:04:21,469
At first glance,

117
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:25,722
this document seems like a guideline
on flood control from Inchon,

118
00:04:25,723 --> 00:04:28,725
<i>but bold and regular text are mixed.</i>

119
00:04:28,726 --> 00:04:30,519
THE FONT THICKNESS VARIES

120
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:32,020
- Let's see.
- It's a puzzle.

121
00:04:32,021 --> 00:04:32,938
You're right.

122
00:04:32,939 --> 00:04:35,357
"Mutinous…"

123
00:04:35,358 --> 00:04:36,483
- "Faction."
- "Faction."

124
00:04:36,484 --> 00:04:37,985
READING TEXT IN THE REGULAR FONT ONLY

125
00:04:37,986 --> 00:04:38,902
Oh, the mutineers.

126
00:04:38,903 --> 00:04:42,781
"Seizure, classified information."

127
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:45,242
Oh, so they got hold
of the classified information.

128
00:04:45,243 --> 00:04:47,828
- So, the mutineers stole our secrets.
- That's it.

129
00:04:47,829 --> 00:04:49,872
Let's see what comes next. "Leak."

130
00:04:50,915 --> 00:04:53,834
"Leak, emerge…"

131
00:04:53,835 --> 00:04:55,419
Am I reading it right? "Emerge…"

132
00:04:55,420 --> 00:04:58,088
- We have an emergency due to the leak.
- "Emergency."

133
00:04:58,089 --> 00:04:59,423
- "Emergency due to the leak."
- Yes.

134
00:04:59,424 --> 00:05:01,550
- "In light of the emergency…"
- That's "in light of"?

135
00:05:01,551 --> 00:05:02,634
No, it's "inside the XIN."

136
00:05:02,635 --> 00:05:04,219
- You're right.
- "Agent inside the XIN."

137
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:06,138
So, "an agent inside the XIN."

138
00:05:06,139 --> 00:05:07,431
"Cooperation."

139
00:05:07,432 --> 00:05:09,850
"Suspected."

140
00:05:09,851 --> 00:05:11,185
So they suspect an insider job.

141
00:05:11,686 --> 00:05:13,103
An agent betrayed the XIN.

142
00:05:13,104 --> 00:05:14,021
It's an inside job.

143
00:05:14,022 --> 00:05:15,564
- We have a mole?
- One of us…

144
00:05:15,565 --> 00:05:17,357
- Who is it?
- Hey, I know it's you.

145
00:05:17,358 --> 00:05:18,275
It must be you!

146
00:05:18,276 --> 00:05:19,276
Isn't it you, Hye-ri?

147
00:05:19,277 --> 00:05:20,902
- I'm sure it's you.
- I know it's you.

148
00:05:20,903 --> 00:05:22,070
I can see the lies in your eyes.

149
00:05:22,071 --> 00:05:23,488
- You got it wrong.
- There's a mole?

150
00:05:23,489 --> 00:05:25,574
We have a new member this season.

151
00:05:25,575 --> 00:05:26,658
Hey, Gabee!

152
00:05:26,659 --> 00:05:27,784
- No way!
- I knew it.

153
00:05:27,785 --> 00:05:29,453
- It seemed so strange.
- No way I'm a mole.

154
00:05:29,454 --> 00:05:31,997
I swear I'm innocent.
I'm way too green to pull it off.

155
00:05:31,998 --> 00:05:34,166
- They would never give me that role.
- Listen, Gabee.

156
00:05:34,167 --> 00:05:37,878
- You found this in the glove box.
- Because I'm in the front passenger seat.

157
00:05:37,879 --> 00:05:39,921
- You're lying, Fake Teeth.
- Yong-jin, what about you?

158
00:05:39,922 --> 00:05:41,298
- What's your role?
- Hang on.

159
00:05:41,299 --> 00:05:42,674
I'm just a driver.

160
00:05:42,675 --> 00:05:43,592
CRACKING UP

161
00:05:43,593 --> 00:05:46,219
If the traitor is among the six of us,

162
00:05:46,220 --> 00:05:47,596
- you'll regret it.
- Isn't it you?

163
00:05:47,597 --> 00:05:48,513
It's not me.

164
00:05:48,514 --> 00:05:51,349
- I find John the most suspicious.
- Why did you style your hair differently?

165
00:05:51,350 --> 00:05:52,267
Hang on.

166
00:05:52,268 --> 00:05:53,560
- There's more.
- What does it say?

167
00:05:53,561 --> 00:05:55,353
"Plans to trace them."

168
00:05:55,354 --> 00:05:56,939
Next, "Existing."

169
00:05:57,940 --> 00:06:00,359
"Transportation device."

170
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:04,279
- "Out of work."
- "Out of work."

171
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:08,575
- Does this mean we can't use the Chamber?
- We can't use it today.

172
00:06:08,576 --> 00:06:10,994
That's why we have
to drive our way around today.

173
00:06:10,995 --> 00:06:12,662
"Automobile supplied."

174
00:06:12,663 --> 00:06:13,830
- As in this car.
- Right.

175
00:06:13,831 --> 00:06:16,792
Next, "Enter the address."

176
00:06:16,793 --> 00:06:20,712
- Yes?
- "Follow the directions there."

177
00:06:20,713 --> 00:06:24,759
"Once you're there, card…"

178
00:06:25,259 --> 00:06:28,220
"Use the card."

179
00:06:28,221 --> 00:06:30,639
They want us to use this card!

180
00:06:30,640 --> 00:06:33,267
THE CARD'S PURPOSE FINALLY REVEALED

181
00:06:34,268 --> 00:06:35,894
- "Use the card."
- Okay.

182
00:06:35,895 --> 00:06:37,479
Fasten your seat belts.

183
00:06:37,480 --> 00:06:38,731
- How did I do?
- Can we leave now?

184
00:06:39,398 --> 00:06:40,524
- Good job.
- Seat belts, please.

185
00:06:40,525 --> 00:06:42,192
- You have an eye for details.
- Let's go.

186
00:06:42,193 --> 00:06:43,569
- Should we go?
- Hit the road.

187
00:06:44,570 --> 00:06:47,781
- If we really have a mole…
- That can't be true.

188
00:06:47,782 --> 00:06:49,157
- Right?
- It can't be.

189
00:06:49,158 --> 00:06:52,702
- Let's leave them behind.
- If it's anyone, it's probably Do-hoon.

190
00:06:52,703 --> 00:06:55,455
The only people who can pull it off
are John and Hye-ri.

191
00:06:55,456 --> 00:06:57,916
He's right.
No one would give me such responsibility.

192
00:06:57,917 --> 00:06:58,834
She's flattered.

193
00:06:58,835 --> 00:07:00,085
- It's not me.
- What's going on?

194
00:07:00,086 --> 00:07:01,711
John is wearing glasses today.

195
00:07:01,712 --> 00:07:03,755
- It's to shield his eyes.
- I'd love to do it. It sounds fun.

196
00:07:03,756 --> 00:07:06,842
Forgive me for being blunt,
but if you're a mole,

197
00:07:06,843 --> 00:07:07,927
I'll trash your glasses.

198
00:07:08,511 --> 00:07:09,553
Watch it.

199
00:07:09,554 --> 00:07:11,763
Fool us today, and your glasses are lost.

200
00:07:11,764 --> 00:07:14,015
Don't you find his glasses odd?

201
00:07:14,016 --> 00:07:16,018
- I do.
- They seem so suspicious.

202
00:07:16,727 --> 00:07:19,646
- Remember the door in the last episode?
- Yes?

203
00:07:19,647 --> 00:07:21,815
- This isn't like that at all.
- Exactly.

204
00:07:21,816 --> 00:07:23,483
It's nothing like that one.

205
00:07:23,484 --> 00:07:24,401
You're so right.

206
00:07:24,402 --> 00:07:26,862
- We're here.
- I agree.

207
00:07:26,863 --> 00:07:28,989
- This is it.
- Is that a convenience store?

208
00:07:28,990 --> 00:07:30,031
- A convenience store?
- Yes.

209
00:07:30,032 --> 00:07:31,741
- Are you sure?
- The address took us here.

210
00:07:31,742 --> 00:07:33,618
Our destination was a convenience store.

211
00:07:33,619 --> 00:07:36,496
So random, right?
I wondered what we could do there.

212
00:07:36,497 --> 00:07:38,790
<i>We walked in full of suspicion.</i>

213
00:07:38,791 --> 00:07:40,292
- Should we go in?
- This seems to be it.

214
00:07:40,293 --> 00:07:41,668
This is scary.

215
00:07:41,669 --> 00:07:43,129
- Hang on.
- This is it?

216
00:07:43,713 --> 00:07:45,005
- It's a plain store.
- Welcome.

217
00:07:45,006 --> 00:07:46,673
- Hello.
- Hello.

218
00:07:46,674 --> 00:07:47,716
Hello.

219
00:07:47,717 --> 00:07:49,342
Do we have to buy something with the card?

220
00:07:49,343 --> 00:07:51,095
- Maybe that's it.
- That's a good idea.

221
00:07:52,722 --> 00:07:53,722
HALTS

222
00:07:53,723 --> 00:07:54,806
STARTLED GRUNTS

223
00:07:54,807 --> 00:07:56,141
What's the matter?

224
00:07:56,142 --> 00:07:57,142
- What the…
- Tell us.

225
00:07:57,143 --> 00:08:00,353
SHE LOOKS LIKE SHE'D ENJOY JOKES
ABOUT HIGHER EDUCATION

226
00:08:00,354 --> 00:08:01,938
FROZEN AT THE SIGHT OF A FAMILIAR FACE

227
00:08:01,939 --> 00:08:03,566
- I…
- What's up?

228
00:08:04,567 --> 00:08:05,943
Can I help you?

229
00:08:07,069 --> 00:08:08,028
A photo?

230
00:08:08,029 --> 00:08:09,322
You'll help us?

231
00:08:10,072 --> 00:08:12,157
- We've got a card…
- Look at her name tag.

232
00:08:12,158 --> 00:08:14,493
Check out her name.

233
00:08:14,494 --> 00:08:17,621
CLERK LEE HYE-RI

234
00:08:17,622 --> 00:08:18,747
LEE HYE-RI 1, LEE HYE-RI 2

235
00:08:18,748 --> 00:08:19,998
- Hye-ri.
- I'm getting chills.

236
00:08:19,999 --> 00:08:21,875
THE TWO HYE-RIS MEET

237
00:08:21,876 --> 00:08:23,919
Please tell me if you need anything.

238
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:25,837
- Of course.
- How spooky is this?

239
00:08:25,838 --> 00:08:28,798
OVERWHELMED AGENTS COMPLAIN OF HEADACHES

240
00:08:28,799 --> 00:08:30,091
To be honest,

241
00:08:30,092 --> 00:08:33,261
when Yong-jin screamed
about the man with his name last week,

242
00:08:33,262 --> 00:08:34,554
I thought he was making a fuss.

243
00:08:34,555 --> 00:08:37,307
WHEN YONG-JIN 2 APPEARED

244
00:08:37,308 --> 00:08:39,392
HYE-RI REMAINED SURPRISINGLY CALM

245
00:08:39,393 --> 00:08:42,103
UPSETTING YONG-JIN 1 GREATLY

246
00:08:42,104 --> 00:08:44,147
We need to do a role reversal.

247
00:08:44,148 --> 00:08:46,483
HYE-RI IS NOW IN HIS SHOES

248
00:08:46,484 --> 00:08:48,401
- Let me know if you need help.
- Oh, sure.

249
00:08:48,402 --> 00:08:49,778
"Lee Hye-ri."

250
00:08:49,779 --> 00:08:51,613
Her name tag had my exact name.

251
00:08:51,614 --> 00:08:55,075
Seeing another person
with my name really freaked me out.

252
00:08:55,076 --> 00:08:56,451
Could we…

253
00:08:56,452 --> 00:08:57,369
HESITANT

254
00:08:57,370 --> 00:08:58,703
- Do you work here?
- I'm scared.

255
00:08:58,704 --> 00:09:01,249
- Yes.
- Are you a clerk or the store's owner?

256
00:09:01,832 --> 00:09:03,500
- I'm just an employee.
- I see.

257
00:09:03,501 --> 00:09:05,168
So she's a legit employee?

258
00:09:05,169 --> 00:09:06,963
- I am.
- Why don't we find out?

259
00:09:07,547 --> 00:09:09,506
Can I get a pack of cigarettes?

260
00:09:09,507 --> 00:09:11,883
- Can you tell me the brand?
- Let's see if she can ring it up.

261
00:09:11,884 --> 00:09:13,343
Which one do you want?

262
00:09:13,344 --> 00:09:15,554
She can't be just a clerk.
Surely not, right?

263
00:09:15,555 --> 00:09:17,681
We have the card, right?

264
00:09:17,682 --> 00:09:21,351
- Should we buy something?
- She's your doppelgänger.

265
00:09:21,352 --> 00:09:22,686
Let's get something.

266
00:09:22,687 --> 00:09:25,188
- How about those cigarettes, Yong-jin?
- No, thanks. I don't smoke.

267
00:09:25,189 --> 00:09:27,107
- How about cough drops?
- Okay, let's get some cough drops.

268
00:09:27,108 --> 00:09:29,651
- Can we get the pineapple-flavored one?
- Go ahead.

269
00:09:29,652 --> 00:09:30,569
LIST GROWS ONE BY ONE

270
00:09:30,570 --> 00:09:31,695
How about some water?

271
00:09:31,696 --> 00:09:33,029
- Good idea.
- Can we get some water?

272
00:09:33,030 --> 00:09:33,947
- Yes.
- We need it.

273
00:09:33,948 --> 00:09:35,283
How about some beer?

274
00:09:35,783 --> 00:09:37,367
ALL RIGHT, WE'RE HAVING A PARTY

275
00:09:37,368 --> 00:09:39,120
Let's just grab a bottle of water.

276
00:09:39,620 --> 00:09:41,038
Please insert the card.

277
00:09:41,914 --> 00:09:42,999
Will it work?

278
00:09:44,208 --> 00:09:45,709
No, this isn't it.

279
00:09:45,710 --> 00:09:46,668
- It doesn't work?
- No.

280
00:09:46,669 --> 00:09:48,420
It doesn't have a magnetic strip.

281
00:09:48,421 --> 00:09:49,629
- Can you add this too?
- Water?

282
00:09:49,630 --> 00:09:51,047
- We can't.
- We don't have money.

283
00:09:51,048 --> 00:09:51,965
We don't?

284
00:09:51,966 --> 00:09:53,883
- It wasn't a bank card.
- We're broke.

285
00:09:53,884 --> 00:09:56,803
I assumed the card would work.

286
00:09:56,804 --> 00:09:58,263
But I was wrong.

287
00:09:58,264 --> 00:10:01,433
If the card couldn't be used
to purchase items at the store…

288
00:10:01,434 --> 00:10:04,477
It had to have a purpose, right?

289
00:10:04,478 --> 00:10:07,355
So, we searched around the store.

290
00:10:07,356 --> 00:10:08,565
- Hold on.
- Let's find out.

291
00:10:08,566 --> 00:10:10,275
- Where could we use it?
- Sorry.

292
00:10:10,276 --> 00:10:12,068
- We'll have to look around.
- Right.

293
00:10:12,069 --> 00:10:13,112
WHERE CAN THEY USE THE CARD?

294
00:10:15,656 --> 00:10:17,907
Please return the items.

295
00:10:17,908 --> 00:10:20,411
- Please return the items to their shelves.
- Okay.

296
00:10:27,043 --> 00:10:30,128
<i>- Greetings.</i>
- Oh, my.

297
00:10:30,129 --> 00:10:31,379
What is it?

298
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:32,922
What's up?

299
00:10:32,923 --> 00:10:36,134
<i>Please insert your card
to access the information.</i>

300
00:10:36,135 --> 00:10:37,177
This is it.

301
00:10:37,178 --> 00:10:38,345
So this machine was it?

302
00:10:38,346 --> 00:10:39,596
A FAMILIAR VOICE FROM THE ATM

303
00:10:39,597 --> 00:10:40,680
This is wild.

304
00:10:40,681 --> 00:10:42,266
INSERTING THE CARD

305
00:10:42,808 --> 00:10:44,644
<i>Your identity has been verified.</i>

306
00:10:45,144 --> 00:10:46,102
That's insane.

307
00:10:46,103 --> 00:10:47,020
BLACK CARD FOUND ITS PLACE

308
00:10:47,021 --> 00:10:48,563
COVERING HER… TEETH

309
00:10:48,564 --> 00:10:49,898
What the heck is this?

310
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:52,067
- Something's coming up.
- My gosh!

311
00:10:52,068 --> 00:10:54,277
HEY! SOMETHING'S COMING UP ON THE SCREEN!

312
00:10:54,278 --> 00:10:56,655
GEUMGANG BANK
PLEASE SELECT A SERVICE

313
00:10:56,656 --> 00:10:59,824
<i>I will now brief you on your mission.</i>

314
00:10:59,825 --> 00:11:01,369
SHRIEKS

315
00:11:19,261 --> 00:11:23,515
AGENTS OF MYSTERY SEASON 2

316
00:11:23,516 --> 00:11:24,432
Something's coming up.

317
00:11:24,433 --> 00:11:28,395
<i>I will now brief you on your mission.</i>

318
00:11:28,396 --> 00:11:29,771
<i>Three days ago,</i>

319
00:11:29,772 --> 00:11:33,233
<i>the founder and CEO of Edison Core,
a multinational space company,</i>

320
00:11:33,234 --> 00:11:36,904
<i>Chairman Illon H. Na was abducted
along with his entourage.</i>

321
00:11:38,114 --> 00:11:39,239
Oh, his bodyguards.

322
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:41,032
<i>Chairman Na is a genius entrepreneur</i>

323
00:11:41,033 --> 00:11:43,952
<i>with PhDs in business,
physics, and biological engineering.</i>

324
00:11:43,953 --> 00:11:46,287
<i>He is also a millionaire.</i>

325
00:11:46,288 --> 00:11:47,288
<i>At the moment,</i>

326
00:11:47,289 --> 00:11:51,126
<i>he is recognized as one of
the world's most influential people.</i>

327
00:11:51,127 --> 00:11:52,502
"Illon H. Na"?

328
00:11:52,503 --> 00:11:57,048
<i>As such, the XIN has classified him
as a person of interest</i>

329
00:11:57,049 --> 00:11:59,426
<i>and monitored his activities ever since.</i>

330
00:11:59,427 --> 00:12:01,428
<i>After tracking his phone signal</i>

331
00:12:01,429 --> 00:12:04,722
<i>and hacking surveillance camera footage
across the nation,</i>

332
00:12:04,723 --> 00:12:08,853
<i>his trail vanished after a final sighting
at a factory near Seoul.</i>

333
00:12:09,812 --> 00:12:14,190
<i>At the moment, the factory is emitting
a strong signal of the X-Electric Wave.</i>

334
00:12:14,191 --> 00:12:17,778
<i>Its strength is the highest on record.</i>

335
00:12:18,320 --> 00:12:22,031
<i>If the cause of the X-Electric Wave
is not addressed,</i>

336
00:12:22,032 --> 00:12:26,161
<i>it could lead to a disaster
that threatens all humankind.</i>

337
00:12:26,162 --> 00:12:27,413
She's looking at us.

338
00:12:29,165 --> 00:12:31,166
- I'm scared. Should I cover this?
- Let's do that.

339
00:12:31,167 --> 00:12:33,001
VOCALIZING TO PREVENT EAVESDROPPING

340
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:35,336
BACKING AWAY

341
00:12:35,337 --> 00:12:37,255
I bet you can't hear it now.

342
00:12:37,256 --> 00:12:40,301
<i>Your mission today
comes with two objectives.</i>

343
00:12:40,843 --> 00:12:45,473
<i>First, find out what has happened
to the missing Chairman Na.</i>

344
00:12:46,056 --> 00:12:49,767
<i>Second, identify the source
of the X-Electric Wave</i>

345
00:12:49,768 --> 00:12:52,270
<i>and neutralize its threat.</i>

346
00:12:52,271 --> 00:12:54,022
The X-Elective Wave? Okay.

347
00:12:54,023 --> 00:12:57,734
<i>To facilitate your investigation,
we'll provide you with a few items.</i>

348
00:12:57,735 --> 00:12:58,651
- Okay.
- It's scary.

349
00:12:58,652 --> 00:13:00,070
- What do we get?
- This gives me chills.

350
00:13:00,779 --> 00:13:02,238
MISSION ITEMS INSTEAD OF CASH

351
00:13:02,239 --> 00:13:03,490
- My gosh.
- We've got some stuff.

352
00:13:03,491 --> 00:13:04,407
Really?

353
00:13:04,408 --> 00:13:05,534
- Yes.
- What the heck are those?

354
00:13:06,327 --> 00:13:08,453
ITEMS FOR THE INVESTIGATION FROM THE ATM

355
00:13:08,454 --> 00:13:09,913
- We have a new address.
- This man…

356
00:13:09,914 --> 00:13:11,873
- That must be Chairman Na.
- Chairman Na.

357
00:13:11,874 --> 00:13:12,957
PHOTOS OF CHAIRMAN NA AND THEIR STOP

358
00:13:12,958 --> 00:13:14,292
We have the address here.

359
00:13:14,293 --> 00:13:17,545
<i>The newly developed X-Wave Detector</i>

360
00:13:17,546 --> 00:13:21,132
<i>has been designed to help you
find the source of the X-Electric Wave.</i>

361
00:13:21,133 --> 00:13:24,511
<i>It will react if you get closer
to the source of the X-Electric Wave.</i>

362
00:13:24,512 --> 00:13:25,845
- Here it is.
- Where?

363
00:13:25,846 --> 00:13:28,056
<i>This will beep when we're close, right?</i>

364
00:13:28,057 --> 00:13:28,973
UPGRADED GADGET

365
00:13:28,974 --> 00:13:32,977
<i>Those behind the abduction
and their purpose remain unclear.</i>

366
00:13:32,978 --> 00:13:36,731
<i>Please take extra care
with your personal safety and security.</i>

367
00:13:36,732 --> 00:13:38,691
- Personal safety and security.
- We lost our headquarters.

368
00:13:38,692 --> 00:13:39,776
Let's be more cautious.

369
00:13:39,777 --> 00:13:41,569
<i>If you're caught in the process,</i>

370
00:13:41,570 --> 00:13:44,948
<i>XIN will deny any knowledge of the mission</i>

371
00:13:44,949 --> 00:13:48,911
<i>regardless of your safety.</i>

372
00:13:49,954 --> 00:13:52,330
- There they go again.
- Do they have to go so far?

373
00:13:52,331 --> 00:13:54,416
<i>I wish you the best of luck.</i>

374
00:13:55,709 --> 00:13:57,086
GEUMGANG BANK
PLEASE SELECT A SERVICE

375
00:13:58,629 --> 00:14:00,839
Please give me 300,000 won
in crisp 50,000 won bills.

376
00:14:01,882 --> 00:14:04,467
Let's go. I was hoping to buy some water.

377
00:14:04,468 --> 00:14:06,970
We heard that Chairman Na was abducted.

378
00:14:06,971 --> 00:14:10,139
But we had no idea why he was abducted.

379
00:14:10,140 --> 00:14:13,685
Who's behind Chairman Na's abduction?

380
00:14:13,686 --> 00:14:15,436
We were given a mission,

381
00:14:15,437 --> 00:14:18,606
so we had to go rescue Chairman Na.

382
00:14:18,607 --> 00:14:20,441
AGENTS HURRYING AWAY

383
00:14:20,442 --> 00:14:22,068
- Goodbye.
- Have a good one.

384
00:14:22,069 --> 00:14:23,653
You're leaving?

385
00:14:23,654 --> 00:14:24,779
- Yes.
- We don't have any money.

386
00:14:24,780 --> 00:14:26,322
I hope you haven't pocketed anything.

387
00:14:26,323 --> 00:14:27,532
- Oh, no.
- Of course not.

388
00:14:27,533 --> 00:14:28,616
- Not at all.
- We mean it.

389
00:14:28,617 --> 00:14:29,868
Don't leave empty-handed next time.

390
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:31,494
- Okay.
- We'll do that.

391
00:14:31,495 --> 00:14:33,121
- We'll pick up loads.
- Thank you.

392
00:14:33,122 --> 00:14:34,999
Thank you, Ms. Lee Hye-ri.

393
00:14:35,541 --> 00:14:37,250
Okay, she reminds me of…

394
00:14:37,251 --> 00:14:38,793
- Goodbye.
- See you.

395
00:14:38,794 --> 00:14:40,628
- Why did you take a peek earlier?
- Goodbye.

396
00:14:40,629 --> 00:14:42,297
Because I work here, of course.

397
00:14:42,298 --> 00:14:44,757
- You had to check what we were doing.
- I guess we're an odd bunch.

398
00:14:44,758 --> 00:14:46,719
You sounded like a thug, Gabee.

399
00:14:47,511 --> 00:14:48,428
I got curious.

400
00:14:48,429 --> 00:14:50,055
"I get it, but why did you take a peek?"

401
00:14:50,556 --> 00:14:52,016
While we were being briefed,

402
00:14:52,641 --> 00:14:54,517
the clerk kept staring at us.

403
00:14:54,518 --> 00:14:55,935
It was so scary.

404
00:14:55,936 --> 00:14:59,606
I could only see half of her face too.

405
00:14:59,607 --> 00:15:02,525
I asked because she filled me
with dread and suspicion.

406
00:15:02,526 --> 00:15:04,069
- I got goose bumps.
- Same here.

407
00:15:05,070 --> 00:15:06,821
- She's still looking at us.
- She's watching us.

408
00:15:06,822 --> 00:15:08,574
- She's still observing us.
- What on earth?

409
00:15:10,159 --> 00:15:11,993
- Oh, jeez.
- Why are you staring at us?

410
00:15:11,994 --> 00:15:12,952
CALM DOWN

411
00:15:12,953 --> 00:15:14,121
Goodbye.

412
00:15:15,164 --> 00:15:16,372
NODS

413
00:15:16,373 --> 00:15:18,291
GOODBYE

414
00:15:18,292 --> 00:15:19,292
Have a good one.

415
00:15:19,293 --> 00:15:21,377
Looking back, we were the odd ones.

416
00:15:21,378 --> 00:15:22,503
SELF-REFLECTING

417
00:15:22,504 --> 00:15:24,380
Turns out I had no idea how we looked.

418
00:15:24,381 --> 00:15:26,341
<i>No wonder she thought we were odd.</i>

419
00:15:26,342 --> 00:15:28,009
<i>We were all dressed the same</i>

420
00:15:28,010 --> 00:15:30,386
<i>and huddled over the ATM while exclaiming.</i>

421
00:15:30,387 --> 00:15:32,680
<i>We tried to pay with a strange card
and left empty-handed.</i>

422
00:15:32,681 --> 00:15:34,098
It turns out we were the strange ones.

423
00:15:34,099 --> 00:15:36,643
CONCLUSION REACHED

424
00:15:36,644 --> 00:15:37,685
I feel bad.

425
00:15:37,686 --> 00:15:39,979
Let's get going.
Did you enter the address?

426
00:15:39,980 --> 00:15:41,522
- Yes, we did.
- Let's go.

427
00:15:41,523 --> 00:15:43,983
- What was the chairman's name again?
- Illon H. Na.

428
00:15:43,984 --> 00:15:45,985
We have to rescue Chairman Na.

429
00:15:45,986 --> 00:15:46,903
That's right.

430
00:15:46,904 --> 00:15:48,821
We have to eliminate
the source of the X-Electric Wave.

431
00:15:48,822 --> 00:15:49,989
- Yes.
- That's right.

432
00:15:49,990 --> 00:15:52,158
- I got so preoccupied with Ms. Lee Hye-ri.
- Same here.

433
00:15:52,159 --> 00:15:54,452
- I didn't hear the message.
- I was so scared.

434
00:15:54,453 --> 00:15:56,329
Seeing our names used this way bugs me.

435
00:15:56,330 --> 00:15:57,288
Same here.

436
00:15:57,289 --> 00:16:00,833
Last week,
there was a man named Lee Yong-jin.

437
00:16:00,834 --> 00:16:02,752
<i>We never got to see his face.</i>

438
00:16:02,753 --> 00:16:05,672
<i>He pretended to help us with our mission</i>

439
00:16:05,673 --> 00:16:07,090
<i>and sabotaged us instead.</i>

440
00:16:07,091 --> 00:16:10,927
It means Lee Hye-ri isn't here by chance.

441
00:16:10,928 --> 00:16:13,054
She must have a secret too.

442
00:16:13,055 --> 00:16:15,723
I have a feeling they're working together.

443
00:16:15,724 --> 00:16:16,933
- Agreed.
- I can't help it.

444
00:16:16,934 --> 00:16:19,102
Maybe the NIX put them up to this.

445
00:16:19,103 --> 00:16:22,314
- That's likely.
- We'll need to be ready for surprises.

446
00:16:23,440 --> 00:16:25,858
What's with all these insights today?

447
00:16:25,859 --> 00:16:27,944
- I wonder.
- You seem suspicious, John.

448
00:16:27,945 --> 00:16:29,821
Like I said, I'm not a mole.

449
00:16:29,822 --> 00:16:30,905
Are you the inside man?

450
00:16:30,906 --> 00:16:33,282
- "Like I said, I'm not a mole."
- You just hit a really high pitch.

451
00:16:33,283 --> 00:16:34,827
It was higher than your singing voice.

452
00:16:35,411 --> 00:16:36,327
He's on edge today.

453
00:16:36,328 --> 00:16:37,412
That's for sure.

454
00:16:37,413 --> 00:16:38,413
- Snappy.
- So prickly.

455
00:16:38,414 --> 00:16:39,707
Maybe he's mad too.

456
00:16:40,749 --> 00:16:43,334
I hope they won't divide us
into groups again.

457
00:16:43,335 --> 00:16:45,044
- Oh, totally.
- That was really…

458
00:16:45,045 --> 00:16:46,045
It made me so sad.

459
00:16:46,046 --> 00:16:48,297
- I felt sad and scared.
- I got so emotional.

460
00:16:48,298 --> 00:16:50,758
We'll need to come up with something.

461
00:16:50,759 --> 00:16:52,593
- Like a secret code?
- Yes.

462
00:16:52,594 --> 00:16:54,053
What if… Think about it.

463
00:16:54,054 --> 00:16:55,555
If we're in complete darkness

464
00:16:55,556 --> 00:16:58,433
or if we're communicating
with walkie-talkies from separate rooms,

465
00:16:58,434 --> 00:17:00,435
- they may pretend to be me.
- That's a possibility.

466
00:17:00,436 --> 00:17:01,686
They may tweak their voice and say,

467
00:17:01,687 --> 00:17:03,855
- "Hey, I'm Hye-ri."
- Exactly.

468
00:17:03,856 --> 00:17:06,274
If we can come up with a code
while we're now…

469
00:17:06,275 --> 00:17:07,817
- What should it be?
- "While we're now"?

470
00:17:07,818 --> 00:17:08,818
"While we're now."

471
00:17:08,819 --> 00:17:10,069
We can use that as our code.

472
00:17:10,070 --> 00:17:11,988
- How's "while we're now"?
- I like it.

473
00:17:11,989 --> 00:17:14,365
- That's neat.
- Yes, let's roll with that.

474
00:17:14,366 --> 00:17:15,491
WEIRDLY PERFECT TEAMWORK

475
00:17:15,492 --> 00:17:16,409
HE'S GIVEN UP

476
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:18,286
- "While we're now"?
- We're using that as the code?

477
00:17:18,287 --> 00:17:20,288
"Let's make one now while we're together."

478
00:17:20,289 --> 00:17:22,290
- Shortened into our code.
- "While we're now."

479
00:17:22,291 --> 00:17:24,333
If I say "While we're…"
you have to say "now."

480
00:17:24,334 --> 00:17:25,501
- That's a good idea.
- Okay.

481
00:17:25,502 --> 00:17:27,003
When I say "While we're…" you go "now."

482
00:17:27,004 --> 00:17:29,047
We could end up forgetting it later.

483
00:17:29,048 --> 00:17:31,049
Do you recall the emergency partition?

484
00:17:31,050 --> 00:17:32,175
EMERGENCY PARTITION EPISODE FROM SEASON 1

485
00:17:32,176 --> 00:17:33,676
- Hurry!
- Close the docking room door!

486
00:17:33,677 --> 00:17:34,802
- Behold!
- Behold!

487
00:17:34,803 --> 00:17:36,179
- Close the partition!
- What was it called?

488
00:17:36,180 --> 00:17:37,096
Behold.

489
00:17:37,097 --> 00:17:38,807
I kept saying "emergency parliament."

490
00:17:39,641 --> 00:17:40,976
Right, the emergency parliament.

491
00:17:42,478 --> 00:17:43,978
What was it again? Emergency…

492
00:17:43,979 --> 00:17:45,104
- Partition.
- Partition?

493
00:17:45,105 --> 00:17:46,439
I still don't get it.

494
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:47,523
"While we're now"? Good.

495
00:17:47,524 --> 00:17:48,691
- "While we're now."
- That's it.

496
00:17:48,692 --> 00:17:50,735
- When I say "While we're…" you go "now."
- "While we're now."

497
00:17:50,736 --> 00:17:52,028
Can I see it, Yong-jin?

498
00:17:52,029 --> 00:17:54,655
- Yes, it gives off a sinister vibe.
- What's up with that photo?

499
00:17:54,656 --> 00:17:56,449
- We're heading to this place.
- Right.

500
00:17:56,450 --> 00:17:57,825
This is our next destination.

501
00:17:57,826 --> 00:18:00,161
Why did they take the photo at night?
It's so scary.

502
00:18:00,162 --> 00:18:01,329
The place looks so off.

503
00:18:01,330 --> 00:18:03,207
Why is it leading us onto a narrow road?

504
00:18:04,041 --> 00:18:05,041
Hey, what on earth?

505
00:18:05,042 --> 00:18:07,627
Graves turned up out of the blue.
Why are they here?

506
00:18:07,628 --> 00:18:10,254
- Look at all those graves.
- This is terrifying.

507
00:18:10,255 --> 00:18:12,965
- Those are real, Do-hoon.
- I'm so scared.

508
00:18:12,966 --> 00:18:15,344
WHERE ARE THEY HEADED EXACTLY?

509
00:18:17,179 --> 00:18:18,097
Don't tell me.

510
00:18:18,680 --> 00:18:20,681
- We're visiting an abandoned factory.
- We are.

511
00:18:20,682 --> 00:18:22,642
Hang on, I don't like this.

512
00:18:22,643 --> 00:18:23,977
This is it.

513
00:18:24,478 --> 00:18:25,937
This is really bad.

514
00:18:25,938 --> 00:18:27,396
- You can say that again.
- It's messed up.

515
00:18:27,397 --> 00:18:28,981
- Reminds you of <i>Gonjiam,</i> right?
- Oh, dear.

516
00:18:28,982 --> 00:18:30,692
When we reached our destination…

517
00:18:31,902 --> 00:18:35,863
<i>You could just tell that something bad
would happen to anyone who entered.</i>

518
00:18:35,864 --> 00:18:38,908
<i>It was evident that the place held danger,</i>

519
00:18:38,909 --> 00:18:41,244
<i>but we had no idea what that might be.</i>

520
00:18:41,245 --> 00:18:44,747
That uncertainty put us
under a huge strain.

521
00:18:44,748 --> 00:18:46,833
PARKING CAUTIOUSLY

522
00:18:46,834 --> 00:18:48,584
We're in deep trouble. This is bad.

523
00:18:48,585 --> 00:18:49,837
This is making a sound.

524
00:18:50,379 --> 00:18:51,712
What? It's really working.

525
00:18:51,713 --> 00:18:54,465
- It's sensing the X-Electric Wave.
- It must be picking up the signal.

526
00:18:54,466 --> 00:18:56,342
<i>The handheld X-Wave Detector</i>

527
00:18:56,343 --> 00:18:59,595
<i>will react if you get closer
to the source of the X-Electric Wave.</i>

528
00:18:59,596 --> 00:19:01,139
The reading says 29 percent.

529
00:19:01,140 --> 00:19:04,392
- So the strength is at 29 percent?
- What happens when it reaches 100?

530
00:19:04,393 --> 00:19:06,645
We'll need to watch this as we go.

531
00:19:07,771 --> 00:19:09,355
- Let's do this!
- We've got this.

532
00:19:09,356 --> 00:19:10,314
Just a second.

533
00:19:10,315 --> 00:19:11,232
While we're…

534
00:19:11,233 --> 00:19:12,483
- Now!
- Okay, we're good.

535
00:19:12,484 --> 00:19:14,944
It feels like a huge challenge lies ahead.

536
00:19:14,945 --> 00:19:17,446
Let's not push each other around today.

537
00:19:17,447 --> 00:19:19,449
- No pushing around.
- Let's look out for each other.

538
00:19:22,077 --> 00:19:23,286
What a bad vibe.

539
00:19:23,287 --> 00:19:24,495
You can say that again.

540
00:19:24,496 --> 00:19:25,872
The gate has been locked.

541
00:19:25,873 --> 00:19:26,998
We've got locks here.

542
00:19:26,999 --> 00:19:27,833
We'll need keys.

543
00:19:29,501 --> 00:19:30,668
Won't this open?

544
00:19:30,669 --> 00:19:31,628
SIDE DOOR SPOTTED

545
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:35,132
- We have to unlock that.
- We have a lock here.

546
00:19:35,757 --> 00:19:36,966
It's open here.

547
00:19:36,967 --> 00:19:38,134
- Really?
- Yes.

548
00:19:38,135 --> 00:19:39,552
That one was open?

549
00:19:39,553 --> 00:19:41,346
We almost climbed up the gate.

550
00:19:42,431 --> 00:19:43,347
Hello.

551
00:19:43,348 --> 00:19:44,265
- Is anyone there?
- Hello.

552
00:19:44,266 --> 00:19:45,433
Is someone inside?

553
00:19:45,434 --> 00:19:46,393
No.

554
00:19:50,272 --> 00:19:53,901
FAMILIAR TUNE FROM THE OLD RADIO

555
00:19:54,776 --> 00:19:56,402
- Hey, I remember this.
- Hang on.

556
00:19:56,403 --> 00:19:57,820
FEET MOVING TO THE RHYTHM

557
00:19:57,821 --> 00:19:59,071
I got chills.

558
00:19:59,072 --> 00:20:01,365
PTSD TRIGGERED

559
00:20:01,366 --> 00:20:02,825
I hate this.

560
00:20:02,826 --> 00:20:06,370
Maybe this is the NIX
trying to mess with our heads.

561
00:20:06,371 --> 00:20:07,623
- Yes.
- Of course.

562
00:20:08,957 --> 00:20:11,125
I almost thought I was hearing things.

563
00:20:11,126 --> 00:20:12,836
I was sure I couldn't have heard right.

564
00:20:13,337 --> 00:20:17,381
When the radio played the tune,
my feet moved automatically.

565
00:20:17,382 --> 00:20:19,133
AUTO PLAYING

566
00:20:19,134 --> 00:20:20,051
<i>But how could we not?</i>

567
00:20:20,052 --> 00:20:23,638
<i>We worked on that dance
for almost two hours.</i>

568
00:20:23,639 --> 00:20:26,224
HERE'S ONE MORE VICTIM

569
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:28,644
To tell the truth,
I still remember the rhythm.

570
00:20:29,186 --> 00:20:31,729
One, two, three.

571
00:20:31,730 --> 00:20:32,939
One, two. One.

572
00:20:32,940 --> 00:20:35,107
I can recall it from the top of my head.

573
00:20:35,108 --> 00:20:36,692
They're making fun of us.

574
00:20:36,693 --> 00:20:37,693
That's low.

575
00:20:37,694 --> 00:20:40,363
THE YOUNGEST IS STILL EXCITED

576
00:20:40,364 --> 00:20:41,322
Aren't I right?

577
00:20:41,323 --> 00:20:42,531
They're toying with us.

578
00:20:42,532 --> 00:20:43,574
ENTERING THE GUARDHOUSE

579
00:20:43,575 --> 00:20:48,413
GUARDHOUSE

580
00:20:49,581 --> 00:20:52,750
AS EXPECTED IN AN ABANDONED FACTORY,
ALL ITEMS ARE COVERED IN DUST

581
00:20:52,751 --> 00:20:55,169
CHECK ALL AREAS ARE LOCKED BEFORE LEAVING,
RETURN THE KEYS TO THE KEY CABINET

582
00:20:55,170 --> 00:20:57,172
SIGNS OF MANAGEMENT EFFORTS

583
00:20:58,757 --> 00:21:00,968
- I can't stand it, Do-hoon!
<i>- Here are today's top stories.</i>

584
00:21:01,718 --> 00:21:04,053
- I can't stand it, Do-hoon!
<i>- Here are today's top stories.</i>

585
00:21:04,054 --> 00:21:05,763
- Hey, listen.
<i>- Mass communication failure</i>

586
00:21:05,764 --> 00:21:08,849
<i>in and around Seoul is causing
intermittent disruptions…</i>

587
00:21:08,850 --> 00:21:09,934
It's because of that.

588
00:21:09,935 --> 00:21:11,686
- The X-Electric Wave.
- The X-Electric Wave.

589
00:21:11,687 --> 00:21:14,982
<i>The source of the communication failure
hasn't been determined yet…</i>

590
00:21:16,942 --> 00:21:18,193
What? Tell us more.

591
00:21:18,944 --> 00:21:20,152
It got cut off.

592
00:21:20,153 --> 00:21:21,321
This is getting to me.

593
00:21:22,656 --> 00:21:24,448
Yong-jin, there's a key in the cabinet.

594
00:21:24,449 --> 00:21:26,159
- It's locked.
- I saw that too.

595
00:21:26,994 --> 00:21:29,662
There was a key inside the cabinet.

596
00:21:29,663 --> 00:21:32,165
But the cabinet itself was locked.

597
00:21:34,167 --> 00:21:35,251
"All areas are locked…"

598
00:21:35,252 --> 00:21:37,586
"Return the kids…"

599
00:21:37,587 --> 00:21:39,130
Are there any clues in here?

600
00:21:39,131 --> 00:21:40,715
There's a key here,

601
00:21:40,716 --> 00:21:42,425
but we don't know if we'll need it.

602
00:21:42,426 --> 00:21:44,302
First off, the area over there…

603
00:21:44,303 --> 00:21:45,970
The key there might…

604
00:21:45,971 --> 00:21:47,346
JOHN IS STUTTERING A LOT TODAY

605
00:21:47,347 --> 00:21:50,599
"Check all areas are locked
before leaving."

606
00:21:50,600 --> 00:21:52,226
"Return the keys to the key cabinet."

607
00:21:52,227 --> 00:21:53,478
A1 and A2.

608
00:21:54,313 --> 00:21:56,147
Don't they usually put keys down here?

609
00:21:56,148 --> 00:21:57,857
Does it say "A-1," Karina?

610
00:21:57,858 --> 00:21:59,443
- It says A-2.
- A-2?

611
00:22:00,068 --> 00:22:01,235
It's for that door, right?

612
00:22:01,236 --> 00:22:02,486
DOOR NEXT TO THE GUARDHOUSE
A-2

613
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:05,740
CHECKING THE A-2 DOOR

614
00:22:05,741 --> 00:22:07,783
ONLY TO FIND IT LOCKED

615
00:22:07,784 --> 00:22:09,160
We need to take that key out.

616
00:22:09,161 --> 00:22:11,037
- Right? I thought so too.
- And then…

617
00:22:11,038 --> 00:22:13,331
I'm going to imagine I'm the guard.

618
00:22:13,332 --> 00:22:14,750
Then I'll go around this place.

619
00:22:15,625 --> 00:22:16,667
Oh, my joints.

620
00:22:16,668 --> 00:22:17,793
POV: YOU'RE THE GUARD

621
00:22:17,794 --> 00:22:18,711
It must be tiring.

622
00:22:18,712 --> 00:22:19,628
I'LL LOCK THE CABINET

623
00:22:19,629 --> 00:22:20,464
AND TAKE THE KEY…

624
00:22:21,381 --> 00:22:23,632
- I think they would've taken it home.
- Right?

625
00:22:23,633 --> 00:22:25,844
Maybe we have to collect some tools
from elsewhere.

626
00:22:26,386 --> 00:22:27,720
- Possibly.
- It might not be here.

627
00:22:27,721 --> 00:22:29,388
- It looks that way, right?
- Yes.

628
00:22:29,389 --> 00:22:30,848
How about going on patrol duty?

629
00:22:30,849 --> 00:22:32,225
- Let's see if we can find the key.
- Okay.

630
00:22:33,393 --> 00:22:37,480
It's an abandoned house, not a factory.

631
00:22:37,481 --> 00:22:38,732
ABANDONED HOUSE?

632
00:22:39,816 --> 00:22:41,026
<i>I'll come with you.</i>

633
00:22:41,777 --> 00:22:45,488
Which buildings does the map mention
other than the guardhouse?

634
00:22:45,489 --> 00:22:47,114
The factory and office buildings.

635
00:22:47,115 --> 00:22:48,324
That's the office building.

636
00:22:48,325 --> 00:22:50,659
- This is the factory building.
- So this is the factory building?

637
00:22:50,660 --> 00:22:51,661
OFFICE BUILDING, FACTORY BUILDING

638
00:22:53,371 --> 00:22:55,748
- We can't enter that way.
- I don't see an entrance.

639
00:22:55,749 --> 00:22:57,792
FACTORY BUILDING ENTRANCE IS BLOCKED
BY A METAL BARRIER

640
00:22:57,793 --> 00:22:59,168
We have to go that way.

641
00:22:59,169 --> 00:23:00,003
Yes, this is it.

642
00:23:00,587 --> 00:23:02,046
Should we check this place first?

643
00:23:02,047 --> 00:23:03,005
CHECKING THE OFFICE BUILDING DOOR

644
00:23:03,006 --> 00:23:04,423
It's locked.

645
00:23:04,424 --> 00:23:05,633
THIS DOOR IS ALSO LOCKED

646
00:23:05,634 --> 00:23:06,801
To be frank,

647
00:23:06,802 --> 00:23:09,720
<i>I thought we had covered
pretty much all the hiding spots.</i>

648
00:23:09,721 --> 00:23:12,389
<i>The key wasn't in the most likely places.</i>

649
00:23:12,390 --> 00:23:14,975
<i>We still looked around,
thinking the guards might have dropped it.</i>

650
00:23:14,976 --> 00:23:17,645
<i>Even then, we couldn't find it.</i>

651
00:23:17,646 --> 00:23:20,773
- We're back to where we started.
- "A-2."

652
00:23:20,774 --> 00:23:23,151
- The key is nowhere to be found.
- I know.

653
00:23:24,111 --> 00:23:24,986
Why don't we smash it?

654
00:23:25,821 --> 00:23:27,113
- Should we?
- You want to smash it?

655
00:23:27,114 --> 00:23:28,447
- Let's do it.
- What do we do?

656
00:23:28,448 --> 00:23:29,490
Perhaps…

657
00:23:29,491 --> 00:23:31,242
There's a small gap here.

658
00:23:31,243 --> 00:23:32,576
If we can get something thin…

659
00:23:32,577 --> 00:23:33,620
Something like a wire?

660
00:23:34,788 --> 00:23:37,164
RANDOM WIRE OBTAINED

661
00:23:37,165 --> 00:23:38,166
Let me give it a go.

662
00:23:38,750 --> 00:23:40,668
All right. Use that…

663
00:23:40,669 --> 00:23:41,585
LEVERAGING THE GAP

664
00:23:41,586 --> 00:23:43,671
You might be able to get it off the hook.

665
00:23:43,672 --> 00:23:44,588
How?

666
00:23:44,589 --> 00:23:45,756
I'll drop it from the hook.

667
00:23:45,757 --> 00:23:47,341
Then, we can take it out through here.

668
00:23:47,342 --> 00:23:48,301
TAKE IT OUT THROUGH THE GAP BELOW

669
00:23:48,927 --> 00:23:50,011
You startled me, Gabee.

670
00:23:52,097 --> 00:23:53,889
- Hey, I found our tool.
- How do we use it?

671
00:23:53,890 --> 00:23:55,141
Here it is.

672
00:23:55,142 --> 00:23:57,602
A magnet.

673
00:23:58,186 --> 00:23:59,645
WITH A THUNK

674
00:23:59,646 --> 00:24:01,605
- Hey, it's working.
- I think Yong-jin's got it.

675
00:24:01,606 --> 00:24:02,858
- There we go.
- All right!

676
00:24:03,483 --> 00:24:04,317
Let's go.

677
00:24:05,902 --> 00:24:06,944
I did it, didn't I?

678
00:24:06,945 --> 00:24:08,028
COLLECTING THE KEY

679
00:24:08,029 --> 00:24:09,573
KEY A-2 SECURED

680
00:24:11,491 --> 00:24:12,408
As I looked around,

681
00:24:12,409 --> 00:24:14,118
I noticed a magnet
on the fire extinguisher.

682
00:24:14,119 --> 00:24:17,079
The panel was rather pliant,

683
00:24:17,080 --> 00:24:21,375
so I thought we'd be able to drop the key
from its hook by getting the magnet close.

684
00:24:21,376 --> 00:24:23,879
<i>When I put the magnet
on the panel and then removed it,</i>

685
00:24:24,629 --> 00:24:26,797
the key dropped with a clank.

686
00:24:26,798 --> 00:24:28,632
That's my area of expertise.

687
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:30,718
The magnet did the trick, right?
The fire extinguisher.

688
00:24:30,719 --> 00:24:31,635
You're right.

689
00:24:31,636 --> 00:24:34,388
I wondered what a magnet was doing
on the fire extinguisher.

690
00:24:34,389 --> 00:24:36,640
- Let me get the door.
- We're off to a great start.

691
00:24:36,641 --> 00:24:38,101
- I'm opening it.
- Okay.

692
00:24:40,395 --> 00:24:41,271
It worked.

693
00:24:44,774 --> 00:24:46,026
Watch your step, everyone.

694
00:24:48,445 --> 00:24:53,490
OFFICE PANTRY

695
00:24:53,491 --> 00:24:58,245
OLD APPLIANCES SHOWING SIGNS OF AGE

696
00:24:58,246 --> 00:25:02,250
DAILY NECESSITIES FROM LONG AGO
LEFT BEHIND

697
00:25:03,585 --> 00:25:06,503
We have obtained an item.

698
00:25:06,504 --> 00:25:08,505
+1 FLASHLIGHT FOR DO-HOON

699
00:25:08,506 --> 00:25:10,258
- Are the lights not working?
- We'll need it for sure.

700
00:25:11,051 --> 00:25:13,010
- The lights don't work, right?
- They don't work.

701
00:25:13,011 --> 00:25:14,136
It's so spooky.

702
00:25:14,137 --> 00:25:16,597
Shouldn't we arm ourselves?

703
00:25:16,598 --> 00:25:18,933
Like in video games.

704
00:25:18,934 --> 00:25:20,434
- Here's my shield.
- Are there pans?

705
00:25:20,435 --> 00:25:21,852
Let's all grab a weapon.

706
00:25:21,853 --> 00:25:22,770
Like so…

707
00:25:22,771 --> 00:25:23,812
ATTACKING WITHOUT A RESERVE

708
00:25:23,813 --> 00:25:25,314
I guess I like the idea of being armed.

709
00:25:25,315 --> 00:25:28,108
I found myself collecting
items that could do damage.

710
00:25:28,109 --> 00:25:30,736
We might run out of energy.

711
00:25:30,737 --> 00:25:33,615
- Let's take a candy each.
- Don't they look old, though?

712
00:25:34,824 --> 00:25:35,741
Surely not.

713
00:25:35,742 --> 00:25:37,618
I think it's been around for awhile.

714
00:25:37,619 --> 00:25:38,994
- I'll try one later.
- Okay.

715
00:25:38,995 --> 00:25:39,954
CLINICAL TRIAL TO FOLLOW

716
00:25:39,955 --> 00:25:43,082
LOOKING AROUND

717
00:25:43,083 --> 00:25:46,627
JOHN CHECKS THE NEXT ROOM

718
00:25:46,628 --> 00:25:47,795
- All right.
- Is something there?

719
00:25:47,796 --> 00:25:49,463
- The door's open.
- It is?

720
00:25:49,464 --> 00:25:51,716
We'll need to check it out too.

721
00:25:52,509 --> 00:25:53,425
Does it open?

722
00:25:53,426 --> 00:25:54,511
CAREFULLY OPENING THE DOOR

723
00:25:59,557 --> 00:26:01,517
Something tells me we've got to be quiet.

724
00:26:01,518 --> 00:26:06,397
OFFICE

725
00:26:06,398 --> 00:26:08,275
I can't see a thing here.

726
00:26:09,401 --> 00:26:10,818
WITH ONLY THE FLASHLIGHT AS A GUIDE

727
00:26:10,819 --> 00:26:13,362
It's scary, all right.

728
00:26:13,363 --> 00:26:15,364
- It sure is scary.
- It's spooky.

729
00:26:15,365 --> 00:26:16,532
FEAR DRIVING AGENTS TO GRUMBLE

730
00:26:16,533 --> 00:26:18,284
First off, it was pitch dark inside.

731
00:26:18,285 --> 00:26:20,995
<i>The office had an old-school vibe.</i>

732
00:26:20,996 --> 00:26:26,167
<i>All the appliances
and office supplies were worn out.</i>

733
00:26:26,918 --> 00:26:27,835
Just a second.

734
00:26:27,836 --> 00:26:30,754
SEARCH IN THE DARKNESS BEGINS

735
00:26:30,755 --> 00:26:31,839
"Conference room."

736
00:26:31,840 --> 00:26:33,549
CONFERENCE ROOM

737
00:26:33,550 --> 00:26:34,718
This door's locked too.

738
00:26:36,344 --> 00:26:38,972
RELYING ON A FLASHLIGHT
TO CONDUCT A SEARCH

739
00:26:40,015 --> 00:26:41,223
I can't see a thing.

740
00:26:41,224 --> 00:26:42,599
Tell me about it.

741
00:26:42,600 --> 00:26:46,770
<i>I thought that relying on flashlights</i>

742
00:26:46,771 --> 00:26:50,733
<i>couldn't get us so far.</i>

743
00:26:50,734 --> 00:26:54,278
OFFICE PANTRY DOOR IS LEFT OPEN
TO BRING IN WHAT LITTLE LIGHT THERE IS

744
00:26:54,279 --> 00:26:55,612
GLIDING

745
00:26:55,613 --> 00:26:57,656
Why is the door made to close by itself?

746
00:26:57,657 --> 00:26:59,783
<i>It was so dark I could barely see.</i>

747
00:26:59,784 --> 00:27:01,702
<i>I wasn't sure we'd find anything.</i>

748
00:27:01,703 --> 00:27:03,996
<i>Then I noticed an emergency power box.</i>

749
00:27:03,997 --> 00:27:07,625
EMERGENCY POWER BOX

750
00:27:08,793 --> 00:27:09,960
EMERGENCY POWER BOX OPENED

751
00:27:09,961 --> 00:27:11,211
- Everyone.
- What is it?

752
00:27:11,212 --> 00:27:12,463
It's the power box.

753
00:27:12,464 --> 00:27:13,965
Should I switch this on?

754
00:27:14,549 --> 00:27:16,216
Should I switch on the light?

755
00:27:16,217 --> 00:27:17,134
Can we, though?

756
00:27:17,135 --> 00:27:19,887
This seems to be the backup generator.

757
00:27:19,888 --> 00:27:20,804
Really?

758
00:27:20,805 --> 00:27:22,556
<i>There was a backup system.</i>

759
00:27:22,557 --> 00:27:26,352
<i>We found six buttons
when we opened the box.</i>

760
00:27:26,353 --> 00:27:27,895
- Should I switch on the light?
- Should we?

761
00:27:27,896 --> 00:27:30,147
It says you can only press
one button at a time.

762
00:27:30,148 --> 00:27:31,940
EMERGENCY POWER SUPPLIED
WHEN ALL BUTTONS ARE LIT UP

763
00:27:31,941 --> 00:27:33,400
PRESS ONE BUTTON AT A TIME
TO AVOID OVERLOAD

764
00:27:33,401 --> 00:27:34,819
- First button.
- First button?

765
00:27:35,653 --> 00:27:36,653
BUTTON 1 PUSHED

766
00:27:36,654 --> 00:27:37,863
So that's how it works.

767
00:27:37,864 --> 00:27:40,784
- When I press one…
- Do we have to light them all up?

768
00:27:41,701 --> 00:27:44,787
BUTTON 1 CHANGES
THE STATUS OF LIGHTS 1, 2, AND 4

769
00:27:44,788 --> 00:27:45,704
That's how it goes.

770
00:27:45,705 --> 00:27:47,457
Can you try the second button?

771
00:27:48,124 --> 00:27:51,377
BUTTON 2 CHANGES
THE STATUS OF LIGHTS 1, 5, AND 6

772
00:27:51,378 --> 00:27:53,003
There's a set of rules.

773
00:27:53,004 --> 00:27:54,296
- There is.
- Lights 1, 5, and 6.

774
00:27:54,297 --> 00:27:56,298
Hey, 1, 4, 5, 1, 4, 5 should do it.

775
00:27:56,299 --> 00:27:57,257
Try it.

776
00:27:57,258 --> 00:28:00,428
An inspiration hit me like a flash.

777
00:28:00,929 --> 00:28:02,554
- First one?
- Yes, press it.

778
00:28:02,555 --> 00:28:03,473
Fourth one.

779
00:28:03,973 --> 00:28:04,933
Fifth one.

780
00:28:05,475 --> 00:28:07,477
- All the lamps must be turned green.
- Really?

781
00:28:07,977 --> 00:28:10,312
The reverse order should do it, then.

782
00:28:10,313 --> 00:28:11,398
- How?
- Try 5, 4, 1.

783
00:28:11,981 --> 00:28:13,232
All lights turned red with 1, 4, 5,

784
00:28:13,233 --> 00:28:14,651
so they should turn green with 5, 4, 1.

785
00:28:15,151 --> 00:28:16,861
- How did you figure that out?
- It works that way?

786
00:28:18,113 --> 00:28:19,822
- How did you figure that out?
- It works that way?

787
00:28:19,823 --> 00:28:21,073
PUSHING BUTTONS 5, 4, AND 1

788
00:28:21,074 --> 00:28:22,408
THAT DOESN'T WORK

789
00:28:22,409 --> 00:28:23,784
EMBARRASSED GROAN

790
00:28:23,785 --> 00:28:25,160
Don't push yourself forward.

791
00:28:25,161 --> 00:28:25,995
HARSH TREATMENT

792
00:28:28,540 --> 00:28:29,790
FLUSTERED

793
00:28:29,791 --> 00:28:30,917
Two, one, three.

794
00:28:31,459 --> 00:28:33,335
I'll go look somewhere else.
I'm no good here.

795
00:28:33,336 --> 00:28:35,504
GABEE LEAVES THE SCENE

796
00:28:35,505 --> 00:28:36,673
Here's the thing about me.

797
00:28:37,173 --> 00:28:39,884
Quizzes like that aren't my forte.

798
00:28:40,927 --> 00:28:44,555
I usually left that to Hye-ri or John,

799
00:28:44,556 --> 00:28:46,557
while I looked for other clues.

800
00:28:46,558 --> 00:28:48,726
I'll go look around.

801
00:28:48,727 --> 00:28:50,561
I saw a key card lock here, Gabee.

802
00:28:50,562 --> 00:28:52,272
- Did you try our card?
- Not yet.

803
00:28:52,772 --> 00:28:54,815
There's a key card lock.

804
00:28:54,816 --> 00:28:55,733
KEY CARD LOCK

805
00:28:55,734 --> 00:28:57,151
Here's the card, Yong-jin.

806
00:28:57,152 --> 00:28:58,068
TRYING THE PROVIDED ATM CARD

807
00:28:58,069 --> 00:28:59,112
Will it work?

808
00:29:00,238 --> 00:29:01,238
It doesn't, does it?

809
00:29:01,239 --> 00:29:02,698
- No, it doesn't.
- Right?

810
00:29:02,699 --> 00:29:05,325
SEARCH TEAM HAD NO SUCCESS

811
00:29:05,326 --> 00:29:07,703
IN THE MEANTIME,
THE EMERGENCY POWER RECOVERY TEAM

812
00:29:07,704 --> 00:29:09,914
How are we supposed to find the answer?

813
00:29:10,790 --> 00:29:12,916
- It's so difficult.
- This is just…

814
00:29:12,917 --> 00:29:15,170
DEEP IN THOUGHT

815
00:29:15,712 --> 00:29:16,671
This one…

816
00:29:18,339 --> 00:29:21,175
<i>I took a close look
when my teammates pressed the buttons.</i>

817
00:29:21,176 --> 00:29:22,719
Then, I discovered a pattern.

818
00:29:23,553 --> 00:29:25,972
<i>When they tried the buttons one by one,</i>

819
00:29:27,056 --> 00:29:32,437
<i>I saw which button controlled each lamp.</i>

820
00:29:33,605 --> 00:29:35,481
<i>My next task was memorizing them.</i>

821
00:29:35,482 --> 00:29:37,275
<i>Once that's done,</i>

822
00:29:37,859 --> 00:29:38,859
it's just a breeze.

823
00:29:38,860 --> 00:29:41,821
JOHN TO THE RESCUE
AFTER MEMORIZING THE PATTERNS

824
00:29:42,530 --> 00:29:45,240
- This turns on these three lights.
- Yes, 1, 2, and 4.

825
00:29:45,241 --> 00:29:48,161
- This turned on lights 1, 2, and 5.
- So 1, 2, 4 and 1, 5, 6.

826
00:29:48,745 --> 00:29:50,829
I got it. These two will do the trick.

827
00:29:50,830 --> 00:29:53,415
SUCCESS IN JUST A FEW CLICKS

828
00:29:53,416 --> 00:29:54,333
Hey, that did it.

829
00:29:54,334 --> 00:29:55,751
JOHN FINALLY TURNED ON THE LIGHTS

830
00:29:55,752 --> 00:29:57,044
- Nice.
- Totally.

831
00:29:57,045 --> 00:29:59,713
The whole team was badly traumatized

832
00:29:59,714 --> 00:30:03,258
from running into the fake Lee Yong-jin
in the darkness last week.

833
00:30:03,259 --> 00:30:06,011
<i>So, having the lights on soothed us.</i>

834
00:30:06,012 --> 00:30:07,137
<i>We even got the AC on.</i>

835
00:30:07,138 --> 00:30:09,431
<i>The abandoned factory was really hot.</i>

836
00:30:09,432 --> 00:30:10,724
Hey, the AC's working too.

837
00:30:10,725 --> 00:30:12,935
- This is amazing.
- Let's enjoy the cold air a bit.

838
00:30:12,936 --> 00:30:15,103
EVERYONE GATHER AROUND THE AC!

839
00:30:15,104 --> 00:30:17,065
Here's the AC. Great.

840
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:22,027
What I loved the most
was that we had the AC running.

841
00:30:22,028 --> 00:30:24,155
I felt so grateful toward John.

842
00:30:25,657 --> 00:30:27,033
<i>It's the height of summer.</i>

843
00:30:27,742 --> 00:30:30,202
Thanks to the AC,

844
00:30:30,203 --> 00:30:32,538
<i>we could find clues in comfort
if only for a short time.</i>

845
00:30:32,539 --> 00:30:33,831
Man, it's so cool.

846
00:30:33,832 --> 00:30:35,791
ENJOYING THE LUXURY
OF BEING SURROUNDED BY COLD AIR

847
00:30:35,792 --> 00:30:37,459
I'm loving this.

848
00:30:37,460 --> 00:30:38,670
The AC rules.

849
00:30:39,212 --> 00:30:40,588
Karina, the lock's turned on.

850
00:30:41,381 --> 00:30:43,173
- Should we try it now?
- It's finally turned on.

851
00:30:43,174 --> 00:30:45,133
- Which one? The key card lock.
- The one from earlier.

852
00:30:45,134 --> 00:30:48,805
TRYING THE CARD AGAIN

853
00:30:49,430 --> 00:30:52,141
I don't think this is it.
We'll have to find an employee ID.

854
00:30:52,642 --> 00:30:55,395
YOU CAN'T USE THE BLACK CARD
TO SECURE AN ENTRY

855
00:30:56,271 --> 00:30:57,689
I want to crack this door open.

856
00:30:58,356 --> 00:31:00,566
DO-HOON WANTS TO "CRACK"
THE CONFERENCE ROOM DOOR OPEN

857
00:31:00,567 --> 00:31:02,026
Where could it be?

858
00:31:02,694 --> 00:31:05,070
Don't they usually leave the card here?

859
00:31:05,071 --> 00:31:06,281
MONTHLY EVENTS AND PLANS

860
00:31:07,574 --> 00:31:08,866
MAYBE HERE?

861
00:31:08,867 --> 00:31:10,285
NOPE

862
00:31:14,831 --> 00:31:16,415
- Hey, what's that?
- Hang on.

863
00:31:16,416 --> 00:31:18,709
- This looks off.
- Come join us.

864
00:31:18,710 --> 00:31:19,794
- There's blood.
- Blood?

865
00:31:20,545 --> 00:31:22,171
I didn't catch that in the dark.

866
00:31:25,967 --> 00:31:26,884
This is insane.

867
00:31:26,885 --> 00:31:28,677
The bloodstain looks odd.

868
00:31:28,678 --> 00:31:29,761
CLEAR SIGN OF BLOOD UNDER THE BOXES

869
00:31:29,762 --> 00:31:31,263
Why is there blood? Open the black box.

870
00:31:31,264 --> 00:31:32,432
It looks suspicious.

871
00:31:37,270 --> 00:31:39,313
- It's empty.
- Maybe they tried to cover it with boxes?

872
00:31:39,314 --> 00:31:41,398
The pool of blood was pretty huge.

873
00:31:41,399 --> 00:31:43,901
<i>I wondered if a murder had happened.</i>

874
00:31:43,902 --> 00:31:48,196
Could the blood have come from someone
who was murdered in the office?

875
00:31:48,197 --> 00:31:51,825
We'll have to find the employee ID here.

876
00:31:51,826 --> 00:31:54,286
- Right?
- Oh, that could get us entry.

877
00:31:54,287 --> 00:31:55,913
- That's a good approach.
- An employee ID.

878
00:31:55,914 --> 00:31:57,039
Or an ID card of any kind.

879
00:31:57,040 --> 00:31:58,165
SEARCH LIST
EMPLOYEE CARD, ID CARD

880
00:31:58,166 --> 00:31:59,000
Personal information.

881
00:32:00,001 --> 00:32:02,670
LET'S START FROM THESE DRAWERS

882
00:32:03,296 --> 00:32:04,796
- Something has to be here.
- I agree.

883
00:32:04,797 --> 00:32:08,968
GOING THROUGH THE DOCUMENTS FOR CLUES

884
00:32:12,764 --> 00:32:16,099
LEAVING NO STONE UNTURNED

885
00:32:16,100 --> 00:32:20,103
We checked every nook and cranny,

886
00:32:20,104 --> 00:32:23,148
<i>but we couldn't find
even a scrap of paper.</i>

887
00:32:23,149 --> 00:32:26,652
<i>That's when we felt dejected
and powerless.</i>

888
00:32:26,653 --> 00:32:29,322
<i>I must've opened all the boxes
and cabinets I could find.</i>

889
00:32:30,198 --> 00:32:32,157
There's no clue
among all these suspicious things.

890
00:32:32,158 --> 00:32:33,117
CLUES WON'T COME EASILY

891
00:32:33,743 --> 00:32:35,160
DEEP SIGH

892
00:32:35,161 --> 00:32:36,955
This isn't easy.

893
00:32:37,538 --> 00:32:38,789
How annoying is this?

894
00:32:38,790 --> 00:32:40,332
Let's hit the F1 key.

895
00:32:40,333 --> 00:32:41,708
I'll press the F1 button here.

896
00:32:41,709 --> 00:32:43,460
F1.

897
00:32:43,461 --> 00:32:45,420
TAKING A DAY OFF TODAY

898
00:32:45,421 --> 00:32:46,506
What can it be?

899
00:32:47,131 --> 00:32:49,007
- What is it?
- I can't help but wonder

900
00:32:49,008 --> 00:32:51,010
what the clue might be!

901
00:32:54,055 --> 00:32:55,555
Something's off here.

902
00:32:55,556 --> 00:32:57,517
- The french fries?
- They dropped them.

903
00:32:58,977 --> 00:33:01,937
SOMEONE DROPPED FRIES AND SPILLED KETCHUP

904
00:33:01,938 --> 00:33:03,815
There must've been an incident here.

905
00:33:04,565 --> 00:33:06,358
There's no way someone dropped fries.

906
00:33:06,359 --> 00:33:07,235
Why not?

907
00:33:07,902 --> 00:33:09,861
Why do you say it wouldn't happen?

908
00:33:09,862 --> 00:33:11,238
HAS GABEE NEVER DROPPED FRIES BEFORE?

909
00:33:11,239 --> 00:33:12,990
- Something's off here.
- Agreed.

910
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:14,616
They must've been abducted while eating.

911
00:33:14,617 --> 00:33:17,160
- They were eating and got dragged away?
- Yes.

912
00:33:17,161 --> 00:33:20,456
- This is definitely suspicious.
- This does look odd.

913
00:33:22,291 --> 00:33:24,126
The whole team must've had fries.

914
00:33:24,127 --> 00:33:25,168
Some leftovers are here too.

915
00:33:25,169 --> 00:33:26,461
They must've had a team dinner.

916
00:33:26,462 --> 00:33:27,379
Think about it.

917
00:33:27,380 --> 00:33:29,548
If we end up stuck in here for two days,

918
00:33:29,549 --> 00:33:31,216
we'll have to eat those fries.

919
00:33:31,217 --> 00:33:32,217
HORRIFIED

920
00:33:32,218 --> 00:33:34,011
- You feel me, right?
- I'm ready.

921
00:33:34,012 --> 00:33:36,680
- We have to do that to survive.
- Let's decide by rock-paper-scissors.

922
00:33:36,681 --> 00:33:37,639
The winner can have it.

923
00:33:37,640 --> 00:33:38,890
I'm sure I can stomach it.

924
00:33:38,891 --> 00:33:41,643
We'll have to eat the candies
in the pantry as well.

925
00:33:41,644 --> 00:33:43,061
I'm not going to eat them.

926
00:33:43,062 --> 00:33:44,396
LAST RESORT

927
00:33:44,397 --> 00:33:45,606
<i>That's disgusting.</i>

928
00:33:47,275 --> 00:33:48,400
Jeez, the stench.

929
00:33:48,401 --> 00:33:51,029
HYE-RI INSPECTS THE FRIES SCENE

930
00:33:51,821 --> 00:33:52,738
KNOCKING

931
00:33:52,739 --> 00:33:53,906
PUSHING AND KNOCKING

932
00:34:03,291 --> 00:34:05,417
<i>While comparing the drawers,</i>

933
00:34:05,418 --> 00:34:09,255
I noticed that one had a different depth.

934
00:34:11,382 --> 00:34:12,841
<i>The depth was different…</i>

935
00:34:12,842 --> 00:34:13,759
STRANGELY SHALLOW

936
00:34:13,760 --> 00:34:15,177
<i>How should I phrase it?</i>

937
00:34:15,178 --> 00:34:16,387
It sounded different too.

938
00:34:18,264 --> 00:34:19,807
- This feels suspicious.
- Agreed.

939
00:34:20,558 --> 00:34:21,809
- This drawer?
- Yes.

940
00:34:24,854 --> 00:34:27,355
PUZZLED GROAN

941
00:34:27,356 --> 00:34:31,568
A certain drawer caught my eye.

942
00:34:31,569 --> 00:34:34,237
I pounded on it countless times.

943
00:34:34,238 --> 00:34:36,364
I tried it from underneath
and from the sides.

944
00:34:36,365 --> 00:34:37,283
THUMP

945
00:34:38,493 --> 00:34:40,410
THUNK, THUNK, THUNK, SLAM

946
00:34:40,411 --> 00:34:41,579
But I couldn't get it open.

947
00:34:42,747 --> 00:34:45,791
Why can't I crack it open?

948
00:34:45,792 --> 00:34:47,794
- You think that's odd too, right?
- Yes.

949
00:34:48,544 --> 00:34:50,505
- It sure is off.
- Why won't it open?

950
00:34:51,005 --> 00:34:52,965
Maybe this will do the trick.
Open, sesame.

951
00:34:53,466 --> 00:34:55,092
- Behold.
- Open, sesame.

952
00:34:55,093 --> 00:34:56,635
Behold, open the drawer for us.

953
00:34:56,636 --> 00:34:57,636
USING FORCE

954
00:34:57,637 --> 00:34:59,221
Maybe we'll have to…

955
00:34:59,222 --> 00:35:00,430
But it's just…

956
00:35:00,431 --> 00:35:02,390
<i>The splattered ketchup looked so strange.</i>

957
00:35:02,391 --> 00:35:04,559
It would normally fall in a straight line.

958
00:35:04,560 --> 00:35:06,061
But around the button,

959
00:35:06,062 --> 00:35:08,939
<i>you could see the trail
curved at an angle.</i>

960
00:35:08,940 --> 00:35:11,566
Could the ketchup trail have taken a turn?
But that made no sense.

961
00:35:11,567 --> 00:35:13,318
GABEE IS QUESTIONING THE KETCHUP'S COURSE

962
00:35:13,319 --> 00:35:14,654
This is strange.

963
00:35:17,073 --> 00:35:18,074
So strange.

964
00:35:18,574 --> 00:35:20,201
Can't we smash it open?

965
00:35:21,494 --> 00:35:22,870
- What is it?
- The knob goes in!

966
00:35:23,663 --> 00:35:25,163
- What is it?
- The knob goes in!

967
00:35:25,164 --> 00:35:26,623
The knob goes in when I press it!

968
00:35:26,624 --> 00:35:27,541
All out of the blue?

969
00:35:27,542 --> 00:35:28,542
- What?
- It moves.

970
00:35:28,543 --> 00:35:29,501
- It moves?
- Yes.

971
00:35:29,502 --> 00:35:31,044
It responds to pressure.

972
00:35:31,045 --> 00:35:32,671
The other knobs didn't budge,

973
00:35:32,672 --> 00:35:35,257
<i>but that knob moved when I pressed it.</i>

974
00:35:35,258 --> 00:35:36,425
Can you press and turn it?

975
00:35:37,468 --> 00:35:38,635
Are you for real?

976
00:35:38,636 --> 00:35:40,846
This does seem the fishiest.

977
00:35:40,847 --> 00:35:42,764
CONFERENCE ROOM

978
00:35:42,765 --> 00:35:46,226
TURN THE KNOB
TO GET THE KETCHUP TRAIL ALIGNED

979
00:35:46,227 --> 00:35:48,478
AND THE SECRET DRAWER OPENS

980
00:35:48,479 --> 00:35:50,063
- The conference room key.
- It's wild.

981
00:35:50,064 --> 00:35:50,981
CONFERENCE ROOM KEY OBTAINED

982
00:35:50,982 --> 00:35:52,482
This is incredible.

983
00:35:52,483 --> 00:35:54,025
Something's off here.

984
00:35:54,026 --> 00:35:57,362
THE NEWBIE NEVER LOST HER SUSPICION
ABOUT THE FRIES AND THE KETCHUP

985
00:35:57,363 --> 00:35:59,614
- This is definitely suspicious.
- This does look odd.

986
00:35:59,615 --> 00:36:02,075
SHE STAYED AT THE "CRIME SCENE"
AND DELIVERED RESULTS

987
00:36:02,076 --> 00:36:03,118
Gabee.

988
00:36:03,119 --> 00:36:04,203
You rock, Gabee.

989
00:36:05,496 --> 00:36:08,623
- Gabee, you've got great instincts.
- Yes, not that I did much.

990
00:36:08,624 --> 00:36:11,042
- We couldn't find anything.
- You're amazing.

991
00:36:11,043 --> 00:36:13,253
We should keep digging
into the most suspicious item of the day.

992
00:36:13,254 --> 00:36:15,589
I've learned a valuable lesson
regarding suspicious items.

993
00:36:15,590 --> 00:36:18,550
I'll push and turn them from now on.

994
00:36:18,551 --> 00:36:22,596
She said no one eats fries like this.

995
00:36:22,597 --> 00:36:25,098
- She said that from the start.
- No one would drop them like this.

996
00:36:25,099 --> 00:36:26,183
- You're right.
- This is crazy.

997
00:36:26,184 --> 00:36:27,267
Do the honors, Gabee.

998
00:36:27,268 --> 00:36:29,269
- Go ahead, Gabee.
- Can I really do that?

999
00:36:29,270 --> 00:36:30,395
Of course.

1000
00:36:30,396 --> 00:36:31,938
This is the first time I'm opening a door

1001
00:36:31,939 --> 00:36:33,107
- ever since joining you.
- Really?

1002
00:36:42,533 --> 00:36:43,450
What is that?

1003
00:36:43,451 --> 00:36:46,119
- What the hell?
- I got chills!

1004
00:36:46,120 --> 00:36:49,831
POSTERS PLASTERED ALL ACROSS THE WALL

1005
00:36:49,832 --> 00:36:53,501
WITH PHOTOS OF A FAMOUS GIRL GROUP

1006
00:36:53,502 --> 00:36:57,131
A CERTAIN MEMBER APPEARS MORE THAN OTHERS

1007
00:36:59,800 --> 00:37:01,636
I was so astonished.

1008
00:37:02,678 --> 00:37:06,139
It felt like
my double life had been exposed.

1009
00:37:06,140 --> 00:37:09,185
The moment the door opened,
posters for "Dirty Work" greeted us.

1010
00:37:09,977 --> 00:37:11,102
I couldn't grasp it.

1011
00:37:11,103 --> 00:37:12,604
Let's take them off, Karina.

1012
00:37:12,605 --> 00:37:14,481
- That's one too many for a normal fan.
- What on earth?

1013
00:37:14,482 --> 00:37:17,192
It was scary
how the whole wall was covered up.

1014
00:37:17,193 --> 00:37:18,985
I wondered if they were fans of Karina's.

1015
00:37:18,986 --> 00:37:20,111
"Do they love her that much?"

1016
00:37:20,112 --> 00:37:22,405
"Maybe they're a huge fan of aespa."

1017
00:37:22,406 --> 00:37:26,117
Then again, I couldn't help but think
that the photos were arranged so sloppily.

1018
00:37:26,118 --> 00:37:28,120
- You look amazing in the photos, though.
- Really?

1019
00:37:28,829 --> 00:37:30,372
You look so pretty, Karina.

1020
00:37:30,373 --> 00:37:31,331
You're beautiful.

1021
00:37:31,332 --> 00:37:33,333
- How do you look so fine?
- I wonder who she is.

1022
00:37:33,334 --> 00:37:34,876
This is Karina's side job, right?

1023
00:37:34,877 --> 00:37:36,336
- That's true.
- Right?

1024
00:37:36,337 --> 00:37:38,338
The other girls are also members, right?

1025
00:37:38,339 --> 00:37:39,881
- They're my colleagues.
- Right.

1026
00:37:39,882 --> 00:37:43,219
<i>Since it was our photo,
I was a bit happy and took a closer look.</i>

1027
00:37:45,054 --> 00:37:46,931
I found a slight crack in the middle.

1028
00:37:47,598 --> 00:37:50,934
FEELING FOR THE CRACK

1029
00:37:50,935 --> 00:37:52,061
Are there doors here?

1030
00:37:53,980 --> 00:37:56,398
It looks like we've got doors here.

1031
00:37:56,399 --> 00:37:59,151
BEHIND THE HAPHAZARDLY PLASTERED POSTERS

1032
00:38:00,194 --> 00:38:02,446
A FAINT CRACK IS VISIBLE

1033
00:38:05,032 --> 00:38:07,367
COVERED SLIDING DOORS

1034
00:38:07,368 --> 00:38:09,828
This must have a mechanism of sorts.

1035
00:38:09,829 --> 00:38:11,621
- It feels like there'd be a button, right?
- Yes.

1036
00:38:11,622 --> 00:38:13,873
It might open if we said, "I love Karina."

1037
00:38:13,874 --> 00:38:16,293
- Something like the AI "Behold"?
- Behold!

1038
00:38:16,294 --> 00:38:18,003
- What if we dance together?
- Okay.

1039
00:38:18,004 --> 00:38:20,338
- Whose dance are we covering?
- The one you created.

1040
00:38:20,339 --> 00:38:21,424
How about "Whiplash"?

1041
00:38:22,049 --> 00:38:24,092
THEY TRIED EVERYTHING
FROM "WHIPLASH" TO "SUPERNOVA"

1042
00:38:24,093 --> 00:38:25,343
Why won't it work?

1043
00:38:25,344 --> 00:38:26,386
What could it be?

1044
00:38:26,387 --> 00:38:28,513
Open, sesame!

1045
00:38:28,514 --> 00:38:29,724
You have such a strong voice.

1046
00:38:30,308 --> 00:38:35,145
WHAT DO THEY HAVE TO DO TO OPEN THE DOORS?

1047
00:38:35,146 --> 00:38:37,605
The 110 V power outlets stood out to me.

1048
00:38:37,606 --> 00:38:39,357
The power outlets were for 110 V,

1049
00:38:39,358 --> 00:38:41,526
<i>but the plug of the fan was for 220 V.</i>

1050
00:38:41,527 --> 00:38:44,321
I wondered,
"Does this mean we can use it or not?"

1051
00:38:44,322 --> 00:38:48,742
YONG-JIN CHECKS THE FAN

1052
00:38:48,743 --> 00:38:52,037
AND THEN THE PLUG OF THE AC

1053
00:38:52,038 --> 00:38:58,126
I found the AC really odd
because its plug was for 110 V.

1054
00:38:58,127 --> 00:38:59,836
<i>When I plugged it in, the AC worked.</i>

1055
00:38:59,837 --> 00:39:01,379
AC TURNED ON

1056
00:39:01,380 --> 00:39:04,507
I thought that the fan would work too.

1057
00:39:04,508 --> 00:39:06,968
<i>So, I removed the voltage converter</i>

1058
00:39:06,969 --> 00:39:08,762
<i>and used it on the fan's plug to start it.</i>

1059
00:39:08,763 --> 00:39:11,681
<i>But when the fan didn't work,</i>

1060
00:39:11,682 --> 00:39:13,933
I wondered if it was designed this way.

1061
00:39:13,934 --> 00:39:17,187
This is the factory owner's office, right?

1062
00:39:17,188 --> 00:39:19,440
- It's the conference room only in name.
- Everybody, silent.

1063
00:39:28,366 --> 00:39:29,783
I think I heard a scream.

1064
00:39:29,784 --> 00:39:30,784
- What?
- Or maybe not.

1065
00:39:30,785 --> 00:39:31,701
- Or so I hope.
- Come on.

1066
00:39:31,702 --> 00:39:33,037
- You're driving us insane.
- Sorry.

1067
00:39:50,096 --> 00:39:51,805
OBLIVIOUS TO THE SITUATION OUTSIDE
AND RESUMING THE SEARCH

1068
00:39:51,806 --> 00:39:52,847
Who owned this jacket?

1069
00:39:52,848 --> 00:39:54,849
Would the doors open if one of us wore it?

1070
00:39:54,850 --> 00:39:55,850
That can't be, right?

1071
00:39:55,851 --> 00:39:57,352
- To pretend to be the owner?
- Yes.

1072
00:39:57,353 --> 00:39:58,853
Try it, Do-hoon.

1073
00:39:58,854 --> 00:40:00,021
Pretend to be the owner here.

1074
00:40:00,022 --> 00:40:01,398
RIPPING SOUNDS

1075
00:40:01,399 --> 00:40:04,527
REMOVING THE POSTERS WITHOUT HESITATION

1076
00:40:06,821 --> 00:40:08,822
SO CLEAN

1077
00:40:08,823 --> 00:40:09,906
John, do you have to…

1078
00:40:09,907 --> 00:40:11,032
HURT

1079
00:40:11,033 --> 00:40:12,493
Do you have to be so inconsiderate?

1080
00:40:13,160 --> 00:40:14,369
You're not this person.

1081
00:40:14,370 --> 00:40:15,620
RATIONALIZING HIS ACTIONS

1082
00:40:15,621 --> 00:40:16,914
Do you have to be so inconsiderate?

1083
00:40:17,873 --> 00:40:19,291
I'M OUT

1084
00:40:20,084 --> 00:40:21,751
That's a sure way to hurt her feelings.

1085
00:40:21,752 --> 00:40:26,297
Seeing John tear down
my team's posters without any hesitation

1086
00:40:26,298 --> 00:40:28,007
made things clear for me.

1087
00:40:28,008 --> 00:40:30,135
He had to be the mole within the XIN.

1088
00:40:30,136 --> 00:40:32,178
You were giving a father

1089
00:40:32,179 --> 00:40:35,598
storming into his son's room
and taking down his posters of Karina.

1090
00:40:35,599 --> 00:40:37,600
- "Focus on your studies!"
- The boy was a bad student.

1091
00:40:37,601 --> 00:40:39,269
He'd yell, "You brat!"

1092
00:40:39,270 --> 00:40:40,229
"You brat!"

1093
00:40:41,188 --> 00:40:43,314
Karina, it looks off.

1094
00:40:43,315 --> 00:40:44,692
Still, I put it back on.

1095
00:40:46,152 --> 00:40:47,403
It's up again, sorry.

1096
00:40:48,070 --> 00:40:49,946
Hey, what's this?

1097
00:40:49,947 --> 00:40:51,657
110 V POWER OUTLETS AND PLUG
YONG-JIN TRIED EARLIER

1098
00:40:53,367 --> 00:40:56,035
I plugged it in,
but it wouldn't quite fit.

1099
00:40:56,036 --> 00:40:57,203
<i>So, I was moving it around.</i>

1100
00:40:57,204 --> 00:40:58,497
CLICK

1101
00:41:00,332 --> 00:41:01,333
I removed this cover.

1102
00:41:02,126 --> 00:41:03,751
- You removed it?
- That startled me.

1103
00:41:03,752 --> 00:41:05,420
- I pressed it and it opened.
- It slid open.

1104
00:41:05,421 --> 00:41:06,921
- Nice.
- Well done.

1105
00:41:06,922 --> 00:41:09,674
- It caught me by surprise.
- Great job.

1106
00:41:09,675 --> 00:41:11,051
You're the best, Do-hoon.

1107
00:41:13,262 --> 00:41:14,345
Isn't it…

1108
00:41:14,346 --> 00:41:15,680
- Oh, man.
- This is so…

1109
00:41:15,681 --> 00:41:19,059
ONCE THE SECRET DOORS OPENED
THANKS TO DO-HOON'S EFFORTS

1110
00:41:19,643 --> 00:41:22,396
<i>It was a plan to abduct Chairman Na.</i>

1111
00:41:23,105 --> 00:41:25,274
<i>The whole blueprint was right there.</i>

1112
00:41:29,737 --> 00:41:31,196
There we have it.

1113
00:41:31,197 --> 00:41:32,614
- They planned it all out.
- For sure.

1114
00:41:32,615 --> 00:41:34,407
- It was premeditated.
- Exactly.

1115
00:41:34,408 --> 00:41:37,160
What could these plans A and B mean?

1116
00:41:37,161 --> 00:41:41,039
<i>The abduction plan was written in detail.</i>

1117
00:41:41,040 --> 00:41:44,584
<i>It clearly laid out where
and how they would abduct him.</i>

1118
00:41:44,585 --> 00:41:47,546
METICULOUSLY PLANNED CRIME

1119
00:41:48,130 --> 00:41:49,547
Do we have to move again?

1120
00:41:49,548 --> 00:41:50,673
- It was a huge op.
- What's this?

1121
00:41:50,674 --> 00:41:53,636
- That must be how they grabbed him.
- They sure love fries.

1122
00:41:55,095 --> 00:41:58,556
They mapped out Illon H. Na's every move

1123
00:41:58,557 --> 00:42:02,644
<i>and were obsessively tracking him down.</i>

1124
00:42:02,645 --> 00:42:04,145
VISITS THE TEA HOUSE SOMETIMES

1125
00:42:04,146 --> 00:42:05,063
Chairman Na.

1126
00:42:05,064 --> 00:42:05,980
RESIDENCE IN THE US

1127
00:42:05,981 --> 00:42:09,400
According to this,
they attached a tracker to Chairman Na.

1128
00:42:09,401 --> 00:42:11,277
In other words,

1129
00:42:11,278 --> 00:42:14,614
they abducted him
after figuring out where he frequents.

1130
00:42:14,615 --> 00:42:17,700
INFORMATION OBTAINED SO FAR

1131
00:42:17,701 --> 00:42:20,411
1. THEY HAD A METICULOUS ABDUCTION PLAN

1132
00:42:20,412 --> 00:42:23,081
2. THEY HAD A TRACKER ON ILLON H. NA

1133
00:42:23,082 --> 00:42:24,165
Look here.

1134
00:42:24,166 --> 00:42:26,000
They singled out Song Bodyguard
to keep an eye on.

1135
00:42:26,001 --> 00:42:27,669
PARK SECURITY

1136
00:42:27,670 --> 00:42:30,630
We have Kim Secretary
and the head of security.

1137
00:42:30,631 --> 00:42:32,258
<i>"What's Up with Kim Secretary?"</i>

1138
00:42:34,051 --> 00:42:35,261
It's the title of that TV show.

1139
00:42:36,804 --> 00:42:38,596
<i>Another thing that stood out to me</i>

1140
00:42:38,597 --> 00:42:40,974
<i>was this phrase in a document
that was stamped "top secret."</i>

1141
00:42:40,975 --> 00:42:44,227
It said that a black security bag
was a high priority.

1142
00:42:44,228 --> 00:42:45,729
"A black security case."

1143
00:42:46,313 --> 00:42:47,855
That must mean a lot.

1144
00:42:47,856 --> 00:42:50,066
They have obtained intel
that Chairman Na would travel

1145
00:42:50,067 --> 00:42:53,611
while personally carrying
the black security case.

1146
00:42:53,612 --> 00:42:56,364
They wanted to carry out their plan
on that exact occasion.

1147
00:42:56,365 --> 00:42:59,784
The abductors' objective
might be Chairman Na,

1148
00:42:59,785 --> 00:43:02,078
but they might have brought him here

1149
00:43:02,079 --> 00:43:05,124
<i>to secure a very important item
he was carrying.</i>

1150
00:43:05,624 --> 00:43:07,625
It lists the abandoned factory
as the current location.

1151
00:43:07,626 --> 00:43:09,460
They plan to keep him here.

1152
00:43:09,461 --> 00:43:11,796
- "To be sequestered here." He's here.
- He must be here somewhere.

1153
00:43:11,797 --> 00:43:13,923
- Yes, he must be here.
- We drove to 35 Gyeongwa-ro.

1154
00:43:13,924 --> 00:43:15,174
- Right.
- It's here.

1155
00:43:15,175 --> 00:43:16,092
He's here, then.

1156
00:43:16,093 --> 00:43:19,470
They must be holding him here somewhere.

1157
00:43:19,471 --> 00:43:20,388
- All hidden.
- Objectives…

1158
00:43:20,389 --> 00:43:22,265
- He must be in the factory building.
- Right.

1159
00:43:22,266 --> 00:43:24,225
<i>-He might be.
- That's pretty likely.</i>

1160
00:43:24,226 --> 00:43:25,893
IS CHAIRMAN NA IN THE FACTORY BUILDING?

1161
00:43:25,894 --> 00:43:27,270
We managed to open the doors.

1162
00:43:27,271 --> 00:43:30,315
Since we've done that,
we'll have to move to another location.

1163
00:43:30,316 --> 00:43:31,691
To go somewhere else,

1164
00:43:31,692 --> 00:43:33,067
we'll need some other tools, right?

1165
00:43:33,068 --> 00:43:35,695
- Yes, we'll need to unlock another door.
- Right.

1166
00:43:35,696 --> 00:43:38,532
THEY HAVEN'T FOUND A WAY
TO GET PAST THIS KEY CARD LOCK

1167
00:43:39,950 --> 00:43:41,744
- Nothing's here.
- No?

1168
00:43:42,661 --> 00:43:44,954
REVISITING ALL THE PLACES

1169
00:43:44,955 --> 00:43:49,250
THEY HAVE SEARCHED BEFORE

1170
00:43:49,251 --> 00:43:52,254
Nothing stands out to me.
It's worse than earlier.

1171
00:43:55,174 --> 00:43:56,799
It only had fries inside, right?

1172
00:43:56,800 --> 00:43:57,759
TRASH CAN FROM EARLIER

1173
00:43:57,760 --> 00:43:58,927
Can you check it again, John?

1174
00:44:00,763 --> 00:44:02,096
- Hey.
- There's a card.

1175
00:44:02,097 --> 00:44:03,306
- There's a card?
- You found one?

1176
00:44:03,307 --> 00:44:04,265
Where is it?

1177
00:44:04,266 --> 00:44:05,558
All I saw were fries.

1178
00:44:05,559 --> 00:44:08,061
They must've cut it in half
to prevent us from finding it.

1179
00:44:08,062 --> 00:44:09,646
- Okay, let's go.
- I didn't know it was there.

1180
00:44:09,647 --> 00:44:10,563
- It was there?
- Yes.

1181
00:44:10,564 --> 00:44:13,024
- Let's go.
- I just thought they must love fries.

1182
00:44:13,025 --> 00:44:14,234
It taught me a lesson.

1183
00:44:14,860 --> 00:44:15,943
I wasn't attentive enough.

1184
00:44:15,944 --> 00:44:17,737
I'd better pull myself together.

1185
00:44:17,738 --> 00:44:20,406
I can't believe I missed
what was right in front of me.

1186
00:44:20,407 --> 00:44:22,450
I checked the trash can twice.

1187
00:44:22,451 --> 00:44:24,202
- Let's go, then.
- Okay.

1188
00:44:24,203 --> 00:44:25,536
- Be careful.
- He'll need a flashlight.

1189
00:44:25,537 --> 00:44:27,206
- Flashlights.
- Where are they? I saw one earlier.

1190
00:44:29,416 --> 00:44:31,959
TAKING A PEEK

1191
00:44:31,960 --> 00:44:33,628
- Do you scare easily, John?
- What?

1192
00:44:33,629 --> 00:44:35,089
- Are you a chicken?
- Call me Chicken Park.

1193
00:44:35,714 --> 00:44:37,173
- Chicken Park.
- Chicken Park.

1194
00:44:37,174 --> 00:44:38,174
CARD PIECES IN CHICKEN PARK'S HANDS

1195
00:44:38,175 --> 00:44:39,676
Do you want to attach them with tape?

1196
00:44:39,677 --> 00:44:41,636
- There's tape here in the office.
- Right.

1197
00:44:41,637 --> 00:44:42,929
I brought one here.

1198
00:44:42,930 --> 00:44:47,183
I roamed the office area several times,
so I knew we had tape there.

1199
00:44:47,184 --> 00:44:48,309
ITEM DETECTOR

1200
00:44:48,310 --> 00:44:49,852
Do we need to tape it?

1201
00:44:49,853 --> 00:44:53,106
SWIPING THE TAPE LIKE NOBODY'S BUSINESS

1202
00:44:53,107 --> 00:44:58,112
I suggested repairing the card with tape
and gave it to John.

1203
00:44:58,946 --> 00:45:00,696
RECONSTRUCTION SURGERY BEGINS

1204
00:45:00,697 --> 00:45:01,657
Try it.

1205
00:45:03,617 --> 00:45:05,243
<i>-Authorized.</i>
- Hey, it worked!

1206
00:45:05,244 --> 00:45:06,160
Okay.

1207
00:45:06,161 --> 00:45:06,995
AUTHENTICATION SUCCESSFUL

1208
00:45:13,001 --> 00:45:14,293
There is blood.

1209
00:45:14,294 --> 00:45:15,586
I see blood.

1210
00:45:15,587 --> 00:45:16,754
We have blood, everyone.

1211
00:45:16,755 --> 00:45:20,300
BLOODSTAINS ALL OVER THE FLOOR

1212
00:45:22,010 --> 00:45:24,179
- Look.
- This is just the beginning, everyone.

1213
00:46:53,268 --> 00:46:58,273
Subtitle translation by: Jeongwoo Kim
